{"title_page": "Bilisht", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = mu\n|official_name      = Bilisht\n|image_flag         = \n|emblem             = Stema e Bashkis\u00eb Devoll.svg\n|skyline            = Bilishti.jpg\n|image_caption      = The town centre of Bilisht (2013)\n|image_location     = \n|county             = [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n|municipality       = [[Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Devoll]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|37|39|N|20|59|24|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = 922\n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = \n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 12000\n|postal_code        = 7006\n|area_code          = (0)811\n|website            = \n}}\n'''Bilisht''' ({{lang-al|Bilisht}}) is a town and a former municipality in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]], south-eastern [[Albania]]. At the 2015 local government reform it became a subdivision and the seat of the municipality [[Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Devoll]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |title=Law nr. 115/2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead |access-date=2015-06-11 }}</ref> It was the seat of the former [[Devoll District]]. The population at the 2011 census was 6,250.<ref name=census11>[http://www.instat.gov.al/media/195826/7__korce.pdf 2011 census results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035505/http://www.instat.gov.al/media/195826/7__korce.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The town is 9&nbsp;km from the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]] with [[Greece]] at [[Kapshtic\u00eb]]. The closest Greek village across the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]] is [[Krystallopigi]] in the [[Florina (regional unit)|Florina regional unit]]. Bilisht is at 890 meters above sea level<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> and has a continental climate with cool summers and cold winters. It serves as an economic centre for the local agriculture, mining, food and textile industries.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> The [[football (soccer)|football]] club is [[KS Devolli|Bilisht Sporti]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe town of Bilisht is the most southeastern city of Albania. It is located to the east of the Devoll Valley, about 880-970m above sea level in a hilly relief that stretches from the Devoll River bed to Kokogllava hill over the city and covers an area of 1.4km2. With average altitude 925 m above sea level Bilisht is the second highest city in Albania after Ersek\u00eb (1020m above sea level).\n\nThe city has a very favorable geographic position as it passes through the motorway link connecting Albania with Greece via the Kapshtic\u00eb customs that is 7&nbsp;km east of it. In the north the town is bordered by Bitinck\u00eb (3&nbsp;km east of it), east bounded by the hills of Kokogllava (1140m above sea level), Stranra (1280m above sea level), Sellc\u00eb (an early residence near Bilisht) and V\u00ebrnik, (5&nbsp;km east), south is bordered by Visho\u00e7ic\u00eb (3&nbsp;km south), while west is bordered by Devoll River and villages like Polosk\u00eb (4&nbsp;km), Ku\u00e7 (3&nbsp;km), Baban (5.5&nbsp;km ) and Ho\u00e7isht (6.5&nbsp;km). Bilisht has a population of about 12,000 and is the capital of the Municipality of Devoll.\n\nThe [[T\u00fcrbe|tyrbe]] (tomb) of the Muslim Sufi saint Qazim Baba is located in Bilisht.<ref name=\"Elsie53\">{{cite journal|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=The Christian Saints of Albania|url=http://home.olemiss.edu/~mldyer/balk/article2.html|journal=Balkanistica|volume=13|issue=36|year=2000|pages=53|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate in Bilisht is Mediterranean transient, but with remarkable continental influence. The high sea level (930m), as well as the distance from the sea, makes the summer in Bilisht to be warm and fresh, with a cold and snowy winter, as well as with the fall of fresh autumn.\n\n'''The average annual temperature''' is 9.9 degrees. The hottest month of the year is July with an average of 19.5 degrees C, where the highest and lowest temperatures range from 14 degrees in the night and 26.6 degrees during the day. The coldest month is January with an average of 0.2 degrees, with average temperatures ranging from -3.6 degrees at night and 4.1 degrees during the day. The maximum temperature was reached in July 1988 (39 degrees) while the minimum was reached in January 2012 (-20 degrees). The annual temperature range is 19.3 degrees.\n\nThe '''precipitation''' in Bilisht is lower than in other cities of Albania as a result of the strong continental and mountain ranges that surround this area. The average annual rainfall is 780mm. The largest amount of rainfall is reached in the spring and fall months: November (100mm) and October (89mm). Most of the precipitation is in May where on average there are 15 days of rainfall and 16 days of dryness. The dryest months are August (39mm) and July (40mm). The highest number of dry days is August, where on average there are 23 dry days and 8 days of rainfall In the second half of autumn snowfall begins which falls until April. During the winter the largest amount of snowfall falls, mainly in January (4 days on average) and February (5 days on average). Usually snow precipitation may be present even in the spring months.\n\n'''The frosts''' in Bilisht are present during the 8 months of the year, the month with the highest number of frosts is January (19 days), while the month with fewer days with frost is May (0.1 days) and October (1.3 days)\n\n'''The wind''' at Bilisht is mainly blowing from the west and the north, the month with the highest wind speed is February with March (9&nbsp;km / h), while the lowest speed is August at 6&nbsp;km / h. The largest windmill is March, where the average wind speed averages 5&nbsp;km / h over the course of 15 days, while the less windy month is October, where the wind averaged 5&nbsp;km / h in 7 days.\n\n'''Sunny days and sunset''': The most sunny month is August, where on average there are 13 sunny days and 17 days partly cloudy or wintry, while the waning month is May where on average 25 days are cloudy or partly cloudy and 6 days with Sun.\n\n==History==\nA fortified location dating from the [[early Iron Age]] exists nearby Bilisht.<ref name=\"Hammond6\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Collected studies, Volume III|year=1994|publisher=Adolf M. Hakkert|isbn=978-9025610517|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=1WwiAQAAIAAJ&q=bilisht&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjz38OquNbkAhWaA3IKHd56Aws4ChDoAQgsMAE|pages=6|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nBilisht was part of the [[Ottoman Empire]] for several centuries. Muslims in the [[kaza]] (district) of Bilisht owned tenet farms (ba\u0219tina) in the late 16th century.<ref name=\"Ergo42\">{{cite book|last=Ergo|first=Dritan|chapter=Islam in the Albanian lands (XVth-XVIIth Century)|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMpYPzxNDkAhX2IbcAHRLHC7k4MhDoAQg8MAM#v=onepage&q=Bilisht%20&f=false|pages=42|ref=harv}}</ref> Bilisht became an important centre for the [[Sufism|Sufi]] [[Halveti]] order<ref name=\"Clayer145\">{{cite book|last=Clayer|first=Nathalie|title=L'Albanie, pays des derviches: Les ordres mystiques musulmans en Albanie \u00e0 l'\u00e9poque post-ottomane (1912-1967)|year=1990|publisher=Harrassowitz|isbn=9783447030885|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=31LYAAAAMAAJ&dq=bilishti&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=bilishti|pages=145|ref=harv}}</ref> and maintained two or three [[Khanqah|tekkes]] in the town that were reliant on its tekke in [[Ohrid]].<ref name=\"Elsie90\">{{cite book|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=Handbuch zur albanischen Volkskultur: Mythologie, Religion, Volksglaube, Sitten, Gebr\u00e4uche und kulturelle Besonderheiten|year=2002|publisher=Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=9783447044875|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=eH1pAAAAMAAJ&q=bilisht+tekkes&dq=bilisht+tekkes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJqa2as9PkAhVRjuYKHYf7BEMQ6AEISDAF|pages=90|ref=harv}}</ref> During the [[Great Eastern Crisis]], the [[Treaty of San Stefano]] nearly placed Albanian areas such as Bilisht in a proposed [[Greater Bulgaria|large Bulgarian state]].<ref name=\"Cuaz99\">{{cite journal|last=Cuaz|first=Marco|title=Il tema dell\u2019identit\u00e0 nazionalenella storiografia albanese|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XYWFAAAAIAAJ&dq=san+stefano+Bilisht&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Bilisht|journal=Passato e presente|volume=XIX|issue=39|year=1996|pages=99|ref=harv|doi=}} \"trattato russo-turco di Santo Stefano del 3 marzo 1878 che avrebbe fissato le \u00abindiscutibili frontiere etniche bulgare\u00bb, occupando i territori albanesi di Korcia, Bilisht, Pogradec, Struge, Dib\u00ebr, Gostivar, Ka\u00e7anik e Kumanove.\"</ref> Shortly thereafter it was superseded by the [[Treaty of Berlin (1878)|Treaty of Berlin]] that left the town and its surrounding area in the Ottoman Empire. In the late Ottoman period, the [[Nahiye (Ottoman)|nahiya]] (sub-district) of Bilisht was a centre of revolutionary activity for Albanian and [[Aromanians|Aromanian]] [[cheta]] groups, whom collectively numbered some 150-200 individuals.<ref name=\"VelichkoTrifunov476\">{{cite book|last1=Georgiev|first1=Velichko|last2=Trifunov|first2=Stayko|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 1878-1944 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0422\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0436\u0430|year=1994|publisher=Prosveta|isbn=9789540105581|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WnwvAQAAMAAJ&q=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&dq=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik7bbMrNDkAhXYdCsKHabEAkUQ6AEIbzAJ|pages=476|ref=harv}}</ref> Until the early twentieth century, Bilisht experienced population growth from the surrounding rural area, as it was a centre for artisan activities and trade located on important transport lines.<ref name=\"Vullnetari21\"/> It also made the town vulnerable in times of crisis to robberies and war.<ref name=\"Vullnetari21\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2007|p=21.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Xhamia e Bilishtit 8.jpg|300px|thumb|Mosque of Bilisht]]\nFollowing the [[Balkan Wars]] (1912-1913), Bilisht became part of Albania. Some Muslim Albanian villages on the Greek side of the border had Bilisht as their market town until their inhabitants were sent to [[Turkey]] during the [[Population exchange between Greece and Turkey|Greco-Turkish exchange of populations]] (1923),<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> based on religious criteria. Due to the Albanian census of 1923, the urban status of Bilisht was recognised.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> During the interwar period a tekke of the [[Rifa`i]] Sufi Order existed in Bilisht<ref name=\"Popovic112\">{{cite book|last=Popovic|first=Alexandre|chapter=Les confreries mystiques musulmanes dans liespace albanophone (XIXe-XXe s.)|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMpYPzxNDkAhX2IbcAHRLHC7k4MhDoAQg8MAM#v=onepage&q=Bilisht%20&f=false|pages=112|ref=harv}}</ref> and part of the surrounding Muslim rural population emigrated to [[Australia]].<ref name=\"Vullnetari17\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2007|p=17.}}</ref> Bilisht was also the centre of the Bilisht district.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/>\n\nIn the 1960s, the area around Bilisht and neighboring Kor\u00e7\u00eb had the highest densities of population in mountainous districts within the country (500 metres and above).<ref name=\"Vullnetari75\">{{cite journal|last=Vullnetari|first=Julie|date=September 2007|title=Albanian Migration and Development: State of the art review|url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00291660/document|publisher=IMISCOE (International Migration, Integration and Social Cohesion)|accessdate=14 September 2019|pages=75|ref=harv}}</ref> During the early 1990s, [[Christianity in Albania|Christianity]] and later [[Islam in Albania|Islam]] were revived in Albania.<ref name=\"DeRapper41\"/> As such in Bilisht, the Orthodox church of [[Saint Veneranda]] (Sh\u00ebn e Premte) was rebuilt in 1992 followed by a new mosque in 1995.<ref name=\"DeRapper41\">{{cite journal|last=De Rapper|first=Gilles|title=Religion in post-communist Albania: Muslims, Christians and the concept of 'culture' (Devoll, South Albania)|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=P4xOAQAAIAAJ&q=Bilisht+Islam&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-n87zxdDkAhWGH3AKHcwPBo4Q6AEIVzAI|journal=Anthropological Notebooks|volume=14|issue=2|year=2008|pages=41|ref=harv|doi=}}</ref> The town in post communist Albania has also been a recipient of in-migration by a small number of people from other parts of the country, due to pre-existing family connections.<ref name=\"Vullnetari115209\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2012|pp=115, 209.}}</ref> New shops have opened in Bilisht<ref name=\"Sintes381\">{{cite book|last=Sint\u00e8s|first=Pierre|title=La raison du mouvement: Territoires et r\u00e9seaux de migrants albanais en Gr\u00e8ce|year=2010|publisher=Karthala|isbn=9782811103903|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=VtH0OkaN7F4C&pg=PT389&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrp8LFhdTkAhUx7HMBHW8uAg44HhDoAQhsMAk#v=onepage&q=bilisht&f=false|pages=381|ref=harv}}</ref> and it has been one of a number of towns in the wider area that has attracted investment.<ref name=\"Vullnetari209\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2012|p=209.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nOttoman geographer [[Hadji Khalfa]] (1609-1657) wrote that during the mid seventeenth century the nahiya (sub-district) of Bilisht was populated by a mixed [[Albanians|Albanian]] and [[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] population and the Christian element was declining due to local disturbances and [[Islamization of Albania#Southern Albania|inhabitants converting to Islam]].<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\"/> In the early nineteenth century, the ethnic border between Albanians and the neighbouring Slavic (Bulgarian) population ran close and to the east of Bilisht.<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\"/> Between 1805\u20131807, the British traveller [[William Martin Leake]] passed through the area, referred to the ethnic border and stated that the people of Bilisht spoke [[Albanian language|Albanian]].<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\">{{cite book|last=Gyuzelev|first=Boyan V.|title=\u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438 \u0432 \u0418\u0437\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438|year=2004|publisher=\u0418\u041c\u0418\u0420|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZxoXAQAAIAAJ&q=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&dq=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwij_r_msNDkAhWRbisKHfsDDKgQ6AEIQTAD|pages=67|ref=harv}} \"\u0415\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u044f \u0434\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0449\u0435 \u0432\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0430 XIX \u0432. \u0422\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u00f2 \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0442\u043e\u043a, \u043d\u044f\u043a\u044a\u0434\u0435 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0447\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430. \u0412 1805\u20131807 \u0433. \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437 \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b \u0430\u043d\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043d\u044a\u0442 \u0423\u0438\u043b\u044f\u043c \u041b\u0438\u0439\u043a. \u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430, \u0442\u044a\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043c\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438. \u0412\u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 XVII \u0432. \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u044f\u0442 \u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444 \u0425\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0444\u0430 \u0432 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0431\u0430\u0447\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0437\u0432\u0430, \u0447\u0435 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0445\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0441\u0430 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438. \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0432\u0430\u043b\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0439-\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0439\u0449\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0441\u043b\u044f\u043c\u0430.\"</ref>\n\nAccording to Georgi Trajchev in 1929, Bilisht in 1912-1913 was recorded as having 20 households and 106 inhabitants with the settlement described as a Bulgarian village.<ref>Trajchev, Georgi. [http://www.strumski.com/books/Georgi_Trajchev_BG_Selistha_v_Albania.pdf \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0434\u043d\u0435\u0448\u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f], \u0432: \u041e\u0442\u0435\u0446\u044a \u041f\u0430\u0438\u0441\u0438\u0439, 15-31 \u044e\u043b\u0438 1929 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0441\u0442\u0440.213.</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the population was 5600.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\">{{cite book|last1=Altmann|first1=Franz-Lothar|last2=Elsie|first2=Robert|title=Albanien im Umbruch: eine Bestandsaufnahme|year=1990|publisher=Oldenbourg|isbn=9783486558487|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Cpm4AAAAIAAJ&q=bilisht&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4iK7P99PkAhUkmuYKHfJvBGA4MhDoAQhHMAY|pages=212|ref=harv}}</ref> In post-communist Albania, Bilisht contains a mixed population of Muslims and Orthodox Christians.<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> In 1995, it had 8000 inhabitants<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> and 7000 in 2001.<ref name=\"Vullnetari23\">{{cite book|last=Vullnetari|first=Julie|title=Albania on the move: Links between internal and international migration|year=2012|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|isbn=9789089643551|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JSGPweA2KL8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+migration&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2i7fXztDkAhUBjeYKHefbBlAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=23|ref=harv}}</ref> Apart from the village of [[Vernik|V\u00ebrnik]], all other settlements of the Devoll region including Bilisht are populated by an Albanian speaking population.<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\">{{cite book|last=De Rapper|first=Gilles|chapter=Blood and Seed, Trunk and Hearth: Kinship and Common Origin in southern Albania|editor1-last=Hemming|editor1-first=Andreas|editor2-last=Kera|editor2-first=Gentiana|editor3-last=Pandelejmoni|editor3-first=Enriketa|title=Albania: Family, Society and Culture in the 20th century|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643501448|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA81&dq=Bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig3LPklNDkAhXEX3wKHWIWDT8Q6AEIQzAE#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=80\u201381|ref=harv}}</ref> A [[Romani people in Albania|Romani community]] also exists in the town that settled in Bilisht during the 17th century.<ref name=\"Dalipaj132\">{{cite book|last=Dalipaj|first=Gerda|chapter=Roma communities in Elbasan|editor1-last=Hemming|editor1-first=Andreas|editor2-last=Kera|editor2-first=Gentiana|editor3-last=Pandelejmoni|editor3-first=Enriketa|title=Albania: Family, Society and Culture in the 20th century|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643501448|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA81&dq=Bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig3LPklNDkAhXEX3wKHWIWDT8Q6AEIQzAE#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=132|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe municipal council for Devoll composed of 17 members is located in Bilisht.<ref name=\"muncoucil\"/> In local Albanian elections of the early 2000s, a member of the Romani community was elected to the municipal council as a councilor.<ref name=\"DeSotoBeddiesGedeshi111\">{{cite book|last=De Soto|first=Hermine|last2=Beddies|first2=Sabine|last3=Gedeshi|first3=Ilir|title=Roma and Egyptians in Albania: From social exclusion to social inclusion|year=2005|location=Washington D.C.|publisher=World Bank Publications|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eLDiHsezD8EC&pg=PA16&dq=mixed+marriages+Albania#v=snippet&q=islam&f=false|isbn=9780821361719|pages=111|ref=harv}}</ref> At the [[Albanian local elections, 2011|2011 Albanian local elections]], the Macedonian minority succeeded in electing one councilor to the  municipal council.<ref name=\"muncoucil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cec.org.al/images/stories/zgjedhje-vendore/2011/html_lshumemerore/110919_-_DTI_-_lista_keshill_2011.htm|title=List of elected councilors (2011 local elections of Albania)|year=2011|publisher=[[Central Election Commission of Albania]]|language=Albanian|accessdate=10 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705092257/http://www.cec.org.al/images/stories/zgjedhje-vendore/2011/html_lshumemerore/110919_-_DTI_-_lista_keshill_2011.htm|archivedate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\nIn the early 1990s, the Greek political party [[Omonoia (organization)|Omonia]] in Albania fielded a local candidate from Bilisht in elections, however it was later withdrawn after threats of violence.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bugajski|first1=Janusz|title=Ethnic Politics in Eastern Europe: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315287430|page=72|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=KY0YDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT336&dq=#v=onepage&q=thanasi%20jorgji&f=false=|language=en|quote=Several other anti-Greek incidents are reported on the eve of the elections. For example, Thanasi Jorgji from the village of Bilisht, province of Korce, withdraws his candidacy after local Albanians threatened to burn down his house.}}</ref>\n\n== Popular culture ==\nThe town of Bilisht is the location for events in an [[Albanian iso-polyphony|Albanian polyphonic song]] ''N\u00eb plepat Bilishtit'' (The poplars of Bilisht) that commemorates male bravery, honour and family values.<ref name=\"Sugarman256\">{{cite book|last=Sugarman|first=Jane|title=Engendering song: Singing and subjectivity at Prespa Albanian weddings|year=1997|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226779720|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=d0vZkH0m-bMC&pg=PA256&dq=bilisht+plepat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivn4jJqNPkAhW74XMBHTmiCP8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bilisht%20plepat&f=false|pages=256|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Bilisht 21.jpg|Centre of Bilisht\nFile:Bilisht 26.jpg|Primary school \"Drit\u00ebro Agolli\"\nFile:Bilisht 30.jpg|Elementary school \"Myteza Zyko\"\nFile:Stadiumi \u201cDevolli\u201d n\u00eb Bilisht 1.jpg|\"Devolli\" Stadium\nFile:Bilisht 47.jpg|\"\u00c7ezma e Madhe\" (large water fountain), erected 1914-1918 \nFile:Bilisht 53.jpg|Communist era bunker\nFile:Bilisht 55.jpg|Monument to local victims of communism\nFile:Bilisht 54.jpg|Bilisht and Orthodox Church (far right corner)\nFile:Teqeja Halvetjane, n\u00eb Bilisht 2.jpg|Halveti tekke\nFile:Bilisht 34.jpg|Streetscape in Bilisht\nFile:Bilisht 37.jpg|Houses in Bilisht\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090622174951/http://www.visitdevoll.com/alb_htdocs/default.htm Visit Devoll Tourist Guide]\n* [http://strumski.com/biblioteka/?id=605 \"\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0411\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 (\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0438)\"] , an article on the history of Bilishta, written by the priest Trpo Popovski in 1912 (in Bulgarian).\n\n{{Cities in Albania}}\n{{Kor\u00e7\u00eb County}}\n{{Devoll div}}\n\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Albania\u2013Greece border crossings]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n[[Category:Towns in Albania]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement AL\n|type               = mu\n|official_name      = Bilisht\n|image_flag         = \n|emblem             = Stema e Bashkis\u00eb Devoll.svg\n|skyline            = Bilishti.jpg\n|image_caption      = The town centre of Bilisht (2013)\n|image_location     = \n|county             = [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County|Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n|municipality       = [[Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Devoll]]\n|coordinates        = {{coord|40|37|39|N|20|59|24|E|type:adm1st_region:AL_dim:100000|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation          = 922\n|elevation_min      = \n|elevation_max      = \n|area_total         = \n|population_as_of   = 2011\n|population_total   = 12000\n|postal_code        = 7006\n|area_code          = (0)811\n|website            = \n}}\n'''Bilisht''' ({{lang-al|Bilisht}}) is a town and a former municipality in [[Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]], south-eastern [[Albania]]. At the 2015 local government reform it became a subdivision and the seat of the municipality [[Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb|Devoll]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |title=Law nr. 115/2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924085559/http://www.reformaterritoriale.al/images/presentations/Ligji%20ndarja%20territoriale_Fletore_zyrtare.pdf |archive-date=2015-09-24 |url-status=dead |access-date=2015-06-11 }}</ref> It was the seat of the former [[Devoll District]]. The population at the 2011 census was 6,250.<ref name=census11>[http://www.instat.gov.al/media/195826/7__korce.pdf 2011 census results] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924035505/http://www.instat.gov.al/media/195826/7__korce.pdf |date=2015-09-24 }}</ref> The town is 9&nbsp;km from the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]] with [[Greece]] at [[Kapshtic\u00eb]]. The closest Greek village across the [[Border crossings of Albania|border]] is [[Krystallopigi]] in the [[Florina (regional unit)|Florina regional unit]]. Bilisht is at 890 meters above sea level<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> and has a continental climate with cool summers and cold winters. It serves as an economic centre for the local agriculture, mining, food and textile industries.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> The [[football (soccer)|football]] club is [[KS Devolli|Bilisht Sporti]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe town of Bilisht is the most southeastern city of Albania. It is located to the east of the Devoll Valley, about 880-970m above sea level in a hilly relief that stretches from the Devoll River bed to Kokogllava hill over the city and covers an area of 1.4km2. With average altitude 925 m above sea level Bilisht is the second highest city in Albania after Ersek\u00eb (1020m above sea level).\n\nThe city has a very favorable geographic position as it passes through the motorway link connecting Albania with Greece via the Kapshtic\u00eb customs that is 7&nbsp;km east of it. In the north the town is bordered by Bitinck\u00eb (3&nbsp;km east of it), east bounded by the hills of Kokogllava (1140m above sea level), Stranra (1280m above sea level), Sellc\u00eb (an early residence near Bilisht) and V\u00ebrnik, (5&nbsp;km east), south is bordered by Visho\u00e7ic\u00eb (3&nbsp;km south), while west is bordered by Devoll River and villages like Polosk\u00eb (4&nbsp;km), Ku\u00e7 (3&nbsp;km), Baban (5.5&nbsp;km ) and Ho\u00e7isht (6.5&nbsp;km). Bilisht has a population of about 12,000 and is the capital of the Municipality of Devoll.\n\nThe [[T\u00fcrbe|tyrbe]] (tomb) of the Muslim Sufi saint Qazim Baba is located in Bilisht.<ref name=\"Elsie53\">{{cite journal|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=The Christian Saints of Albania|url=http://home.olemiss.edu/~mldyer/balk/article2.html|journal=Balkanistica|volume=13|issue=36|year=2000|pages=53|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Climate==\nThe climate in Bilisht is Mediterranean transient, but with remarkable continental influence. The high sea level (930m), as well as the distance from the sea, makes the summer in Bilisht to be warm and fresh, with a cold and snowy winter, as well as with the fall of fresh autumn.\n\n'''The average annual temperature''' is 9.9 degrees. The hottest month of the year is July with an average of 19.5 degrees C, where the highest and lowest temperatures range from 14 degrees in the night and 26.6 degrees during the day. The coldest month is January with an average of 0.2 degrees, with average temperatures ranging from -3.6 degrees at night and 4.1 degrees during the day. The maximum temperature was reached in July 1988 (39 degrees) while the minimum was reached in January 2012 (-20 degrees). The annual temperature range is 19.3 degrees.\n\nThe '''precipitation''' in Bilisht is lower than in other cities of Albania as a result of the strong continental and mountain ranges that surround this area. The average annual rainfall is 780mm. The largest amount of rainfall is reached in the spring and fall months: November (100mm) and October (89mm). Most of the precipitation is in May where on average there are 15 days of rainfall and 16 days of dryness. The dryest months are August (39mm) and July (40mm). The highest number of dry days is August, where on average there are 23 dry days and 8 days of rainfall In the second half of autumn snowfall begins which falls until April. During the winter the largest amount of snowfall falls, mainly in January (4 days on average) and February (5 days on average). Usually snow precipitation may be present even in the spring months.\n\n'''The frosts''' in Bilisht are present during the 8 months of the year, the month with the highest number of frosts is January (19 days), while the month with fewer days with frost is May (0.1 days) and October (1.3 days)\n\n'''The wind''' at Bilisht is mainly blowing from the west and the north, the month with the highest wind speed is February with March (9&nbsp;km / h), while the lowest speed is August at 6&nbsp;km / h. The largest windmill is March, where the average wind speed averages 5&nbsp;km / h over the course of 15 days, while the less windy month is October, where the wind averaged 5&nbsp;km / h in 7 days.\n\n'''Sunny days and sunset''': The most sunny month is August, where on average there are 13 sunny days and 17 days partly cloudy or wintry, while the waning month is May where on average 25 days are cloudy or partly cloudy and 6 days with Sun.\n\n==History==\nA fortified location dating from the [[early Iron Age]] exists nearby Bilisht.<ref name=\"Hammond6\">{{cite book|last=Hammond|first=Nicholas Geoffrey Lempri\u00e8re|title=Collected studies, Volume III|year=1994|publisher=Adolf M. Hakkert|isbn=978-9025610517|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=1WwiAQAAIAAJ&q=bilisht&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjz38OquNbkAhWaA3IKHd56Aws4ChDoAQgsMAE|pages=6|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\nBilisht was part of the [[Ottoman Empire]] for several centuries. Muslims in the [[kaza]] (district) of Bilisht owned tenet farms (ba\u0219tina) in the late 16th century.<ref name=\"Ergo42\">{{cite book|last=Ergo|first=Dritan|chapter=Islam in the Albanian lands (XVth-XVIIth Century)|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMpYPzxNDkAhX2IbcAHRLHC7k4MhDoAQg8MAM#v=onepage&q=Bilisht%20&f=false|pages=42|ref=harv}}</ref> Bilisht became an important centre for the [[Sufism|Sufi]] [[Halveti]] order<ref name=\"Clayer145\">{{cite book|last=Clayer|first=Nathalie|title=L'Albanie, pays des derviches: Les ordres mystiques musulmans en Albanie \u00e0 l'\u00e9poque post-ottomane (1912-1967)|year=1990|publisher=Harrassowitz|isbn=9783447030885|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=31LYAAAAMAAJ&dq=bilishti&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=bilishti|pages=145|ref=harv}}</ref> and maintianed two or three [[Khanqah|tekkes]] in the town that were reliant on its tekke in [[Ohrid]].<ref name=\"Elsie90\">{{cite book|last=Elsie|first=Robert|title=Handbuch zur albanischen Volkskultur: Mythologie, Religion, Volksglaube, Sitten, Gebr\u00e4uche und kulturelle Besonderheiten|year=2002|publisher=Harrassowitz Verlag|isbn=9783447044875|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=eH1pAAAAMAAJ&q=bilisht+tekkes&dq=bilisht+tekkes&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiJqa2as9PkAhVRjuYKHYf7BEMQ6AEISDAF|pages=90|ref=harv}}</ref> During the [[Great Eastern Crisis]], the [[Treaty of San Stefano]] nearly placed Albanian areas such as Bilisht in a proposed [[Greater Bulgaria|large Bulgarian state]].<ref name=\"Cuaz99\">{{cite journal|last=Cuaz|first=Marco|title=Il tema dell\u2019identit\u00e0 nazionalenella storiografia albanese|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=XYWFAAAAIAAJ&dq=san+stefano+Bilisht&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Bilisht|journal=Passato e presente|volume=XIX|issue=39|year=1996|pages=99|ref=harv|doi=}} \"trattato russo-turco di Santo Stefano del 3 marzo 1878 che avrebbe fissato le \u00abindiscutibili frontiere etniche bulgare\u00bb, occupando i territori albanesi di Korcia, Bilisht, Pogradec, Struge, Dib\u00ebr, Gostivar, Ka\u00e7anik e Kumanove.\"</ref> Shortly thereafter it was superseded by the [[Treaty of Berlin (1878)|Treaty of Berlin]] that left the town and its surrounding area in the Ottoman Empire. In the late Ottoman period, the [[Nahiye (Ottoman)|nahiya]] (sub-district) of Bilisht was a centre of revolutionary activity for Albanian and [[Aromanians|Aromanian]] [[cheta]] groups, whom collectively numbered some 150-200 individuals.<ref name=\"VelichkoTrifunov476\">{{cite book|last1=Georgiev|first1=Velichko|last2=Trifunov|first2=Stayko|title=\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430 \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 1878-1944 \u0432 \u0434\u043e\u043a\u0443\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0442\u0438: \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0432 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u0422\u0440\u0430\u043a\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u0414\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0443\u0434\u0436\u0430|year=1994|publisher=Prosveta|isbn=9789540105581|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=WnwvAQAAMAAJ&q=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&dq=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwik7bbMrNDkAhXYdCsKHabEAkUQ6AEIbzAJ|pages=476|ref=harv}}</ref> Until the early twentieth century, Bilisht experienced population growth from the surrounding rural area, as it was a centre for artisan activities and trade located on important transport lines.<ref name=\"Vullnetari21\"/> It also made the town vulnerable in times of crisis to robberies and war.<ref name=\"Vullnetari21\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2007|p=21.}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Xhamia e Bilishtit 8.jpg|300px|thumb|Mosque of Bilisht]]\nFollowing the [[Balkan Wars]] (1912-1913), Bilisht became part of Albania. Some Muslim Albanian villages on the Greek side of the border had Bilisht as their market town until their inhabitants were sent to [[Turkey]] during the [[Population exchange between Greece and Turkey|Greco-Turkish exchange of populations]] (1923),<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> based on religious criteria. Due to the Albanian census of 1923, the urban status of Bilisht was recognised.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> During the interwar period a tekke of the [[Rifa`i]] Sufi Order existed in Bilisht<ref name=\"Popovic112\">{{cite book|last=Popovic|first=Alexandre|chapter=Les confreries mystiques musulmanes dans liespace albanophone (XIXe-XXe s.)|editor1-last=Schmitt|editor1-first=Oliver Jens|title=Religion und Kultur im albanischsprachigen S\u00fcdosteuropa &#91;Religion and culture in Albanian-speaking southeastern Europe&#93;|year=2010|location=Frankfurt am Main|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631602959|chapter-url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=aCdYHU9PtiIC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjMpYPzxNDkAhX2IbcAHRLHC7k4MhDoAQg8MAM#v=onepage&q=Bilisht%20&f=false|pages=112|ref=harv}}</ref> and part of the surrounding Muslim rural population emigrated to [[Australia]].<ref name=\"Vullnetari17\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2007|p=17.}}</ref> Bilisht was also the centre of the Bilisht district.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\"/> \n\nIn the 1960s, the area around Bilisht and neighboring Kor\u00e7\u00eb had the highest densities of population in mountainous districts within the country (500 metres and above).<ref name=\"Vullnetari75\">{{cite journal|last=Vullnetari|first=Julie|date=September 2007|title=Albanian Migration and Development: State of the art review|url=https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-00291660/document|publisher=IMISCOE (International Migration, Integration and Social Cohesion)|accessdate=14 September 2019|pages=75|ref=harv}}</ref> During the early 1990s, [[Christianity in Albania|Christianity]] and later [[Islam in Albania|Islam]] were revived in Albania.<ref name=\"DeRapper41\"/> As such in Bilisht, the Orthodox church of [[Saint Veneranda]] (Sh\u00ebn e Premte) was rebuilt in 1992 followed by a new mosque in 1995.<ref name=\"DeRapper41\">{{cite journal|last=De Rapper|first=Gilles|title=Religion in post-communist Albania: Muslims, Christians and the concept of 'culture' (Devoll, South Albania)|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=P4xOAQAAIAAJ&q=Bilisht+Islam&dq=Bilisht+Islam&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-n87zxdDkAhWGH3AKHcwPBo4Q6AEIVzAI|journal=Anthropological Notebooks|volume=14|issue=2|year=2008|pages=41|ref=harv|doi=}}</ref> The town in post communist Albania has also been a recipient of in-migration by a small number of people from other parts of the country, due to pre-existing family connections.<ref name=\"Vullnetari115209\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2012|pp=115, 209.}}</ref> New shops have opened in Bilisht<ref name=\"Sintes381\">{{cite book|last=Sint\u00e8s|first=Pierre|title=La raison du mouvement: Territoires et r\u00e9seaux de migrants albanais en Gr\u00e8ce|year=2010|publisher=Karthala|isbn=9782811103903|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=VtH0OkaN7F4C&pg=PT389&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjrp8LFhdTkAhUx7HMBHW8uAg44HhDoAQhsMAk#v=onepage&q=bilisht&f=false|pages=381|ref=harv}}</ref> and it has been one of a number of towns in the wider area that has attracted investment.<ref name=\"Vullnetari209\">{{harvnb|Vullnetari|2012|p=209.}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nOttoman geographer [[Hadji Khalfa]] (1609-1657) wrote that during the mid seventeenth century the nahiya (sub-district) of Bilisht was populated by a mixed [[Albanians|Albanian]] and [[Bulgarians|Bulgarian]] population and the Christian element was declining due to local disturbances and [[Islamization of Albania#Southern Albania|inhabitants converting to Islam]].<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\"/> In the early nineteenth century, the ethnic border between Albanians and the neighbouring Slavic (Bulgarian) population ran close and to the east of Bilisht.<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\"/> Between 1805-1807, the British traveller [[William Martin Leake]] passed through the area, referred to the ethnic border and stated that the people of Bilisht spoke [[Albanian language|Albanian]].<ref name=\"Gyuzelev67\">{{cite book|last=Gyuzelev|first=Boyan V.|title=\u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438 \u0432 \u0418\u0437\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u0411\u0430\u043b\u043a\u0430\u043d\u0438|year=2004|publisher=\u0418\u041c\u0418\u0420|isbn=|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=ZxoXAQAAIAAJ&q=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&dq=%D0%91%D0%B8%D0%B3%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%89%D0%B0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwij_r_msNDkAhWRbisKHfsDDKgQ6AEIQTAD|pages=67|ref=harv}} \"\u0415\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u043c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0438 \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u044f \u0434\u0432\u0435\u0442\u0435 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0430 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043e\u0449\u0435 \u0432\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0430\u043b\u043e\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0430 XIX \u0432. \u0422\u043e\u0433\u0430\u0432\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430 \u0435 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u0432\u0430\u043b\u0430 \u043f\u00f2 \u043d\u0430 \u0438\u0437\u0442\u043e\u043a, \u043d\u044f\u043a\u044a\u0434\u0435 \u0432 \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0447\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430. \u0412 1805\u20131807 \u0433. \u041f\u0440\u0435\u0437 \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043c\u0438\u043d\u0430\u043b \u0430\u043d\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0438\u043d\u044a\u0442 \u0423\u0438\u043b\u044f\u043c \u041b\u0438\u0439\u043a. \u0421\u043f\u043e\u0440\u0435\u0434 \u043d\u0435\u0433\u043e \u0433\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u0438\u043b\u0430 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0435\u0442\u043e \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430, \u0442\u044a\u0439 \u043a\u0430\u0442\u043e \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043c\u0443 \u0433\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0440\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u0430\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438. \u0412\u0441\u0440\u0435\u0434\u0430\u0442\u0430\u043d\u0430 XVII \u0432. \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u044f\u0442 \u0433\u0435\u043e\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0444 \u0425\u0430\u0434\u0436\u0438 \u041a\u0430\u043b\u0444\u0430 \u0432 \u0441\u0432\u043e\u0435\u0442\u043e \u043e\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0415\u0432\u0440\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0422\u0443\u0440\u0446\u0438\u044f \u043e\u0431\u0430\u0447\u0435 \u043e\u0442\u0431\u0435\u043b\u044f\u0437\u0432\u0430, \u0447\u0435 \u0436\u0438\u0442\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0442\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0445\u0438\u044f \u0411\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0441\u0430 \u0431\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0438 \u0430\u0440\u043d\u0430\u0443\u0442\u0438. \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u044f\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0430\u0437\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430\u043c\u0430\u043b\u044f\u0432\u0430\u043b\u043e \u043d\u0430\u0439-\u0432\u0435\u0447\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u0438\u0437\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u0432 \u0434\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0438 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0439\u0449\u0430 \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u0430\u043d\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0438\u0441\u043b\u044f\u043c\u0430.\"</ref> \n\nAccording to Georgi Trajchev in 1929, Bilisht in 1912-1913 was recorded as having 20 households and 106 inhabitants with the settlement described as a Bulgarian village.<ref>Trajchev, Georgi. [http://www.strumski.com/books/Georgi_Trajchev_BG_Selistha_v_Albania.pdf \u0411\u044a\u043b\u0433\u0430\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0441\u0435\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 \u0432 \u0434\u043d\u0435\u0448\u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0431\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f], \u0432: \u041e\u0442\u0435\u0446\u044a \u041f\u0430\u0438\u0441\u0438\u0439, 15-31 \u044e\u043b\u0438 1929 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0430, \u0441\u0442\u0440.213.</ref>\n\nDuring the 1980s, the population was 5600.<ref name=\"AltmannElsie212\">{{cite book|last1=Altmann|first1=Franz-Lothar|last2=Elsie|first2=Robert|title=Albanien im Umbruch: eine Bestandsaufnahme|year=1990|publisher=Oldenbourg|isbn=9783486558487|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=Cpm4AAAAIAAJ&q=bilisht&dq=bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj4iK7P99PkAhUkmuYKHfJvBGA4MhDoAQhHMAY|pages=212|ref=harv}}</ref> In post-communist Albania, Bilisht contains a mixed population of Muslims and Orthodox Christians.<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> In 1995, it had 8000 inhabitants<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\"/> and 7000 in 2001.<ref name=\"Vullnetari23\">{{cite book|last=Vullnetari|first=Julie|title=Albania on the move: Links between internal and international migration|year=2012|publisher=Amsterdam University Press|isbn=9789089643551|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=JSGPweA2KL8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=Bilisht+migration&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj2i7fXztDkAhUBjeYKHefbBlAQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=23|ref=harv}}</ref> Apart from the village of [[Vernik|V\u00ebrnik]], all other settlements of the Devoll region including Bilisht are populated by an Albanian speaking population.<ref name=\"DeRapper8081\">{{cite book|last=De Rapper|first=Gilles|chapter=Blood and Seed, Trunk and Hearth: Kinship and Common Origin in southern Albania|editor1-last=Hemming|editor1-first=Andreas|editor2-last=Kera|editor2-first=Gentiana|editor3-last=Pandelejmoni|editor3-first=Enriketa|title=Albania: Family, Society and Culture in the 20th century|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643501448|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA81&dq=Bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig3LPklNDkAhXEX3wKHWIWDT8Q6AEIQzAE#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=80-81|ref=harv}}</ref> A [[Romani people in Albania|Romani community]] also exists in the town that settled in Bilisht during the 17th century.<ref name=\"Dalipaj132\">{{cite book|last=Dalipaj|first=Gerda|chapter=Roma communities in Elbasan|editor1-last=Hemming|editor1-first=Andreas|editor2-last=Kera|editor2-first=Gentiana|editor3-last=Pandelejmoni|editor3-first=Enriketa|title=Albania: Family, Society and Culture in the 20th century|year=2012|publisher=LIT Verlag M\u00fcnster|isbn=9783643501448|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=HfpTqhlsCtMC&pg=PA81&dq=Bilisht&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwig3LPklNDkAhXEX3wKHWIWDT8Q6AEIQzAE#v=onepage&q=Bilisht&f=false|pages=132|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Governance==\nThe municipal council for Devoll composed of 17 members is located in Bilisht.<ref name=\"muncoucil\"/> In local Albanian elections of the early 2000s, a member of the Romani community was elected to the municipal council as a councilor.<ref name=\"DeSotoBeddiesGedeshi111\">{{cite book|last=De Soto|first=Hermine|last2=Beddies|first2=Sabine|last3=Gedeshi|first3=Ilir|title=Roma and Egyptians in Albania: From social exclusion to social inclusion|year=2005|location=Washington D.C.|publisher=World Bank Publications|url=https://books.google.com/?id=eLDiHsezD8EC&pg=PA16&dq=mixed+marriages+Albania#v=snippet&q=islam&f=false|isbn=9780821361719|pages=111|ref=harv}}</ref> At the [[Albanian local elections, 2011|2011 Albanian local elections]], the Macedonian minority succeeded in electing one councilor to the  municipal council.<ref name=\"muncoucil\">{{cite web|url=http://www.cec.org.al/images/stories/zgjedhje-vendore/2011/html_lshumemerore/110919_-_DTI_-_lista_keshill_2011.htm|title=List of elected councilors (2011 local elections of Albania)|year=2011|publisher=[[Central Election Commission of Albania]]|language=Albanian|accessdate=10 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705092257/http://www.cec.org.al/images/stories/zgjedhje-vendore/2011/html_lshumemerore/110919_-_DTI_-_lista_keshill_2011.htm|archivedate=5 July 2015}}</ref>\nIn the early 1990s, the Greek political party [[Omonoia (organization)|Omonia]] in Albania fielded a local candidate from Bilisht in elections, however it was later withdrawn after threats of violence.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bugajski|first1=Janusz|title=Ethnic Politics in Eastern Europe: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties: A Guide to Nationality Policies, Organizations and Parties|date=2016|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781315287430|page=72|url=https://books.google.gr/books?id=KY0YDQAAQBAJ&pg=PT336&dq=#v=onepage&q=thanasi%20jorgji&f=false=|language=en|quote=Several other anti-Greek incidents are reported on the eve of the elections. For example, Thanasi Jorgji from the village of Bilisht, province of Korce, withdraws his candidacy after local Albanians threatened to burn down his house.}}</ref> \n\n== Popular culture ==\nThe town of Bilisht is the location for events in an [[Albanian iso-polyphony|Albanian polyphonic song]] ''N\u00eb plepat Bilishtit'' (The poplars of Bilisht) that commemorates male bravery, honour and family values.<ref name=\"Sugarman256\">{{cite book|last=Sugarman|first=Jane|title=Engendering song: Singing and subjectivity at Prespa Albanian weddings|year=1997|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=9780226779720|url=https://books.google.com.au/books?id=d0vZkH0m-bMC&pg=PA256&dq=bilisht+plepat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwivn4jJqNPkAhW74XMBHTmiCP8Q6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=bilisht%20plepat&f=false|pages=256|ref=harv}}</ref> \n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:Bilisht 21.jpg|Centre of Bilisht\nFile:Bilisht 26.jpg|Primary school \"Drit\u00ebro Agolli\"\nFile:Bilisht 30.jpg|Elementary school \"Myteza Zyko\"\nFile:Stadiumi \u201cDevolli\u201d n\u00eb Bilisht 1.jpg|\"Devolli\" Stadium\nFile:Bilisht 47.jpg|\"\u00c7ezma e Madhe\" (large water fountain), erected 1914-1918 \nFile:Bilisht 53.jpg|Communist era bunker\nFile:Bilisht 55.jpg|Monument to local victims of communism\nFile:Bilisht 54.jpg|Bilisht and Orthodox Church (far right corner)\nFile:Teqeja Halvetjane, n\u00eb Bilisht 2.jpg|Halveti tekke\nFile:Bilisht 34.jpg|Streetscape in Bilisht\nFile:Bilisht 37.jpg|Houses in Bilisht\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090622174951/http://www.visitdevoll.com/alb_htdocs/default.htm Visit Devoll Tourist Guide]\n* [http://strumski.com/biblioteka/?id=605 \"\u0413\u0440\u0430\u0434 \u0411\u0438\u043b\u0438\u0449\u0430 (\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0431\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0436\u043a\u0438)\"] , an article on the history of Bilishta, written by the priest Trpo Popovski in 1912 (in Bulgarian).\n\n{{Cities in Albania}}\n{{Kor\u00e7\u00eb County}}\n{{Devoll div}}\n\n[[Category:Former municipalities in Kor\u00e7\u00eb County]]\n[[Category:Albania\u2013Greece border crossings]]\n[[Category:Administrative units of Devoll, Kor\u00e7\u00eb]]\n[[Category:Towns in Albania]]\n", "name_user": "Nat965", "label": "safe", "comment": "ApplyGen fix(es),typo(s) fixed: maintianed \u2192 maintained, 1805-1807 \u2192 1805\u20131807", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bilisht"}
{"title_page": "Olaf Schwarz", "text_new": "{{short description|German canoeist}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = \n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = German\n| sport          = [[Canoeing]]\n| event          = [[Wildwater canoeing]]\n| retired        = \n| club           = VFW Oberalster\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|4|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Germany]]\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCount|total=no\n| [[Wildwater Canoeing World Championships|World Championships]] | 0 | 2 | 0\n}}\n}}\n'''Olaf Schwarz''' (born 2 April 1969) is a former West German male [[Canoeing|canoeist]] who was twice silver medalist in [[Canadian (canoe)|Canadian]] C1 at senior level at the [[Wildwater Canoeing World Championships]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canoeresults.eu/view-results/wildwater|title=World and European Championships Results from 1959 to 2019|publisher=canoeresults.eu|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External likns==\n* [http://www.downriver.de/Sportler/olaf/olafscreen.html Olaf Schwarz] at Down River\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schwarz, Olaf}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:German male canoeists]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Germany-canoe-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|German canoeist}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| headercolor    = \n| name           = \n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = German\n| sport          = [[Canoeing]]\n| event          = [[Wildwater canoeing]]\n| retired        = \n| club           = VFW Oberalster\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1969|4|2|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = [[Germany]]\n| height         = \n| weight         = \n| show-medals    = yes\n| medaltemplate