{"title_page": "Richmond Green", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{for2|the park and sports centre in Richmond Hill, Ontario, Canada|[[Richmond Green (Richmond Hill, Ontario)]]}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Richmond Green\n| photo = Fountain_Richmond_Green.jpg\n| photo_width = 150\n| photo_caption = [[Listed building|Grade II listed]]<ref name=\"Fountain\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065308  |desc=Drinking fountain at south corner of the Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> [[drinking fountain]] on Richmond Green\n| type = [[Village green]]\n| location = [[London]]\n| area = 12 acres\n| created = \n| operator = [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n| status = Open all year\n}}\n'''Richmond Green''' is a recreation area located near the centre of [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], a town of about 20,000 inhabitants situated in south west [[London]]. Owned by the [[Crown Estate]], it is leased to the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]].<ref name=\"Wilkie1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/old_deer_park_richmond_1_20.pdf |format=pdf |title=Old Deer Park Richmond: Landscape Strategy |publisher=Kim Wilkie Associates |date=September 1999|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> The Green, which has been described as \"one of the most beautiful urban greens surviving anywhere in England\",<ref name=\"Cherry and Pevsner\">{{cite book | title=[[The Buildings of England]]&nbsp;\u2013 London 2: South | publisher=[[Penguin Books]] | author=[[Bridget Cherry|Cherry, Bridget]] and [[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner, Nikolaus]] | year=1983 | location=London | page=521 | isbn=0-14-0710-47-7}}</ref> is essentially square in shape and its open grassland, framed with [[broadleaf tree]]s, extends to roughly twelve [[acres]]. On the north-east side there is also a smaller open space called '''Little Green'''.<ref name=\"Old Palace Lane\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_old_palace_lane_to_the_old_deer_park_gates.htm| title=Richmond Green properties: Old Palace Lane to the Old Deer Park Gates | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> Richmond Green and Little Green are overlooked by a mixture of period townhouses, historic buildings and municipal and commercial establishments including the Richmond Lending Library and [[Richmond Theatre]]. On summer weekends and public holidays the Green attracts many residents and visitors. It has a long history of hosting sporting events; from the 16th century onwards tournaments and [[archery]] contests have taken place on the Green, while [[cricket]] matches have occurred since the mid 18th century,<ref name=\"RG Local\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties.htm| title= Richmond Green: Properties| publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> continuing to the present day.\n\n==History and description==\n[[File:Richmond 20931.JPG|thumb|250px|Maids of Honour Row]]\n[[File:Railings at 11 Richmond Green.jpg|thumb|125px|Grade II* listed ornamental iron railings at 11, Richmond Green]]\n[[File:Fragment of the Old Palace, Richmond - geograph.org.uk - 508144.jpg|thumb|175px|Richmond Palace Gate House, which is Grade I listed]]\n[[Jousting]] tournaments took place on Richmond Green in the [[Middle Ages]], when English monarchs were living in or visiting what is now called Richmond.<ref name=\"Friends History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.forg.org.uk/history/ | title=History | publisher=Friends of Richmond Green | accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> For over 400 years, Richmond Green has been edged by houses and commercial premises&nbsp;\u2013 built to provide accommodation for people serving or visiting [[Richmond Palace]]. In 1625 [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] brought his court here to escape the [[Great Plague of London|plague in London]] and by the early 18th century these had become the homes of \"minor nobility, diplomats, and court hangers-on\".<ref name=\"RG Local\"/>\n\nThe construction of the railway in the mid-19th century cut the Green off from [[Old Deer Park]], and led to the building of Victorian [[villa]]s for the more prosperous commuters to London. The [[A316 road]], built in the early 20th century, worsened this separation.\n\nToday the northern, western and southern sides of the Green are residential while the eastern side, linking with Richmond's [[high street]], George Street, is largely retail and commercial. Public buildings line the eastern side of Little Green and pubs and caf\u00e9s cluster in the corner by Paved and Golden Courts&nbsp;\u2013 two of a number of alleys that lead from the Green to George Street. These alleys are lined with mostly privately owned [[boutique]]s.\n\nTo the west of the Green is Old Palace Lane, running gently down to the river.<ref>Robinson, Derek; Fowler, Simon (2017). ''Old Palace Lane: Medieval to Modern Richmond''. [[Richmond Local History Society]] and [[Museum of Richmond]]. {{ISBN|978-0-9550717-9-9}}.</ref> Adjoining to the left is the renowned terrace of well-preserved three-storey houses known as Maids of Honour Row. These were built in 1724 for the [[Maid of honour|maids of honour]] (trusted royal wardrobe servants) of [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]], the [[queen consort]] of [[George II of Great Britain|George II]]. As a child, [[Richard Francis Burton|Richard Burton]], the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] explorer, lived at number 2.<ref name=\"Burton\">{{cite web | url=  https://www.richmond.gov.uk/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/sir_richard_and_lady_isabel_burton| title=Sir Richard Burton (1821\u20131890) and Lady Isabel Burton (1831\u20131896) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local history notes | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Buildings==\nRichmond Green, usually \"The Green\", is also a street address. Numbers 1\u20136, 11\u201312 and 32, Richmond Green are all [[Listed buildings|Grade II* listed]].<ref name=\"1, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065311  |desc=1, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2-6, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065312  |desc=2\u20136, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"No. 11, and Railings\"/><ref name=\"12, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1181111  |desc=12, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"32, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357770  |desc=32, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> Numbers 7\u201310 Richmond Green are all Grade II listed,<ref name=\"Duke Street\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_duke_street_to_brewers_lane.htm | title=Richmond Green properties: Duke Street to Brewers Lane (Greenside) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"7, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065347  |desc=7, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"8 and 9, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1285176  |desc=8 and 9, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"10, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357746  |desc=10, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> as are nos 14\u201318, 21\u201325 and 29\u201331.<ref name=\"Brewers Lane\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_brewers_lane_to_paved_court.htm | title=Richmond Green properties: Brewers Lane to Paved Court (Greenside) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> The [[Ironwork|ornamental iron]] railings at no 11 are Grade II* listed.<ref name=\"No. 11, and Railings\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065348  |desc=No. 11, and Railings|accessdate= 29 September 2016}}</ref> The Cricketers [[public house]] is between 24, Richmond Green and 25, Richmond Green. Another public house, The Prince's Head, is at 28, Richmond Green.<ref name=\"Duke Street\"/> 8, Richmond Green, is the location of the [[Richmond Charities]], which manages Richmond's [[almshouses]].\n\nThe late 19th-century [[drinking fountain]] at the south corner of Richmond Green and a pair of [[Red telephone box|K6 red telephone boxes]] are Grade II listed,<ref name=\"Fountain\"/><ref name=\"Kiosks\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1261332 |desc=Pair of K6 telephone kiosks|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> as is a [[lamp standard]] outside 1, Richmond Green.<ref name=\"Lamp\">{{National Heritage List for England |num= 1357744 |desc=Lamp standard|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe houses on the south-western side of the Green include Maids of Honour Row. The houses, and their gates and railings, at numbers 1\u20134 Maids of Honour Row are Grade I listed.<ref name=\"Maids of Honour list\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065317 |desc=Gates and Railings to Maids of Honour Row/Maids of Honour Row  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The Wardrobe and the Gate House, both [[Listed building|Grade I listed]],<ref name=\"Gate House listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065318 |desc=The Gate House The Old Palace  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Wardrobe listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357730 |desc=The Wardrobe  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> are surviving structures from [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]]'s [[Richmond Palace]]. The Gate House was built in 1501, and was let on a 65-year lease by the [[Crown Estate]] Commissioners in 1986. The Trumpeters' House, which is also Grade I listed,<ref name=\"Trumpeters' House listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357749 |desc=The Trumpeters' House, Old Palace Yard  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> is an early 18th-century house built on the site of Richmond Palace's Middle Gate.\n\nThe street bounding Richmond Green on the north-west is called Pembroke Villas, comprising 5 pairs of large semi-detached Victorian villas, formerly the site of the house of the Dutchman [[Sir Matthew Decker, 1st Baronet]] (1679-1749). It descended to his grandson [[Richard FitzWilliam, 7th Viscount FitzWilliam]] (1745-1816) of [[Mount Merrion]], Dublin, Ireland, who named it \"FitzWilliam House\" and there formed his famous art collection and by his will founded the [[Fitzwilliam Museum]] in Cambridge. The monument to Sir Matthew Decker and Richard FitzWilliam survives against the external wall of St Mary Magdalene's Church, Richmond. FitzWilliam's heir was his cousin [[George Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke]] (1759-1827), of [[Wilton House]] in Wiltshire, who renamed the house \"Pembroke House\". It was demolished in 1840.<ref>[https://www.richmond.gov.uk/richmond_green_old_palace_lane_to_the_old_deer_park_gates]</ref> \nNumbers 1 to 10, Pembroke Villas are Grade II listed.<ref name=\"Pembroke Villas 1-10\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065319 |desc=Pembroke Villas  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The street running along the north east of the Green, where it joins Pembroke Villas, is called Portland Terrace. Numbers 1 to 4, Portland Terrace are Grade II listed.<ref name=\"Portland Terrace 1-4\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357771|desc=Portland Terrace  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Between Pembroke Villas and Portland Terrace is a gate that used to be the entrance to [[Old Deer Park]] and is now open only to pedestrians. Just a few yards beyond the gate, a footbridge crosses the railway to lead to Old Deer Park Car Park. Portland Terrace runs past Little Green to become Duke Street, where [[Duke Street Church, Richmond|Duke Street Church]] is located.\n\n==Cricket on the Green==\n{{Main article|Richmond Green cricket ground}}\n[[File:The Cricketers, The Green, Richmond, Surrey.jpg|thumb|125px|The Cricketers pub]]\nThe Green was a popular venue for [[cricket]] matches during the 18th century and before. The earliest reference to cricket on Richmond Green is from a 1666 letter by [[Sir Robert Paston]], a resident of Richmond.\n\nThe Green is presently home to two [[village cricket]] teams each affiliated to two of Richmond's [[public houses|pubs]], ''The Prince's Head'' and ''The Cricketers''. Midweek matches are contested in the modern limited overs format of [[Twenty20]] usually on a Tuesday or Thursdays, where surrounding village teams compete for the Len Smith Charity Shield.\n\n==Richmond Green in art==\nTwo [[watercolours]]  by Edward Walker, made in 1942, showing nos 10, 11 and 12 Richmond Green<ref name=\"V&A 1\">{{cite web | url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O596336/nos-10-11-12-richmond-watercolour-walker/#.U-eFHvkFGTM.facebook | title=Nos 10, 11 & 12 Richmond Green, Surrey; Recording Britain | publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] | work=Search the collections | accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> and the south side of the Green,<ref name=\"V&A 2\">{{cite web | url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O596335/south-side-of-the-green-drawing-walker/#.U-eEhbwI8d0.facebook | title=South Side of the Green, Richmond; Recording Britain | publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] | work=Search the collection | accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> are in the [[Recording Britain]] collection at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]].\n\n==Societies==\nThe Friends of Richmond Green, an amenity action group, seek to \"protect and enhance the Green for local residents, visitors and future generations\".<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite web | url=http://www.forg.org.uk/ | title=Welcome to the Friends of Richmond Green | publisher=Friends of Richmond Green | accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=165 class=center>\nImage:Richmond Green 5260-6s.jpg|View of the northern half of Richmond Green, showing Pembroke Villas and Portland Terrace\nFile:Splendid Victorian Houses on Richmond Green, London-5057587834.jpg|Houses on Portland Terrace\nFile:Houses_At_Richmond_Green,_London-95369622.jpg|The south corner of Richmond Green\nFile:Richmond Green, London-geograph-2621535-by-Philip-Halling.jpg|Footpaths crossing Richmond Green\nFile:North side of Richmond Green-geograph-2498025-by-Marathon.jpg| Park Gates House, in Pembroke Villas, is next to the old entrance to [[Old Deer Park]]\n</gallery>\n[[Image:Map-richmondgreen.png|thumb|right|150px|Map of Richmond Green]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Richmond Green cricket ground]]\n*[[Richmond Green United Reformed Church]]\n*[[Richmond Palace]]\n*[[Richmond Theatre]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|20em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[John Cloake |Cloake, John]] (2001). ''Richmond Palace: Its History and Its Plan''. [[Richmond Local History Society]]. {{ISBN|978-0952209966}}.\n*[http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties.htm \"Richmond Green properties\", Local history notes, Local Studies Collection, London Borough of Richmond upon Thames, 3 August 2009]\n* Robinson, Derek; Fowler, Simon (2017). ''Old Palace Lane: Medieval to Modern Richmond''. [[Richmond Local History Society]] and [[Museum of Richmond]]. {{ISBN|978-0-9550717-9-9}}.\n*{{cite book|title= The Streets of Richmond and Kew|edition= Third|date=2019|publisher = [[Richmond Local History Society]]}} 140 pages. {{ISBN|978-1912-314010}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.forg.org.uk/ Friends of Richmond Green]\n* [http://www.richmondhistory.org.uk/ Richmond Local History Society]\n* [http://www.richmondsociety.org.uk/ The Richmond Society]\n\n{{LB Richmond}}\n{{Green London}}\n{{coord|51|27|42|N|0|18|25|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conservation areas in London]]\n[[Category:Crown Estate]]\n[[Category:Drinking fountains in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Houses in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Jousting]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Richmond, London]]\n[[Category:Streets in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{for2|the park and sports centre in Richmond Hill, Ontario, Canada|[[Richmond Green (Richmond Hill, Ontario)]]}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Richmond Green\n| photo = Fountain_Richmond_Green.jpg\n| photo_width = 150\n| photo_caption = [[Listed building|Grade II listed]]<ref name=\"Fountain\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065308  |desc=Drinking fountain at south corner of the Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> [[drinking fountain]] on Richmond Green\n| type = [[Village green]]\n| location = [[London]]\n| area = 12 acres\n| created = \n| operator = [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n| status = Open all year\n}}\n'''Richmond Green''' is a recreation area located near the centre of [[Richmond, London|Richmond]], a town of about 20,000 inhabitants situated in south west [[London]]. Owned by the [[Crown Estate]], it is leased to the [[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]].<ref name=\"Wilkie1999\">{{cite web |url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/old_deer_park_richmond_1_20.pdf |format=pdf |title=Old Deer Park Richmond: Landscape Strategy |publisher=Kim Wilkie Associates |date=September 1999|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> The Green, which has been described as \"one of the most beautiful urban greens surviving anywhere in England\",<ref name=\"Cherry and Pevsner\">{{cite book | title=[[The Buildings of England]]&nbsp;\u2013 London 2: South | publisher=[[Penguin Books]] | author=[[Bridget Cherry|Cherry, Bridget]] and [[Nikolaus Pevsner|Pevsner, Nikolaus]] | year=1983 | location=London | page=521 | isbn=0-14-0710-47-7}}</ref> is essentially square in shape and its open grassland, framed with [[broadleaf tree]]s, extends to roughly twelve [[acres]]. On the north-east side there is also a smaller open space called '''Little Green'''.<ref name=\"Old Palace Lane\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_old_palace_lane_to_the_old_deer_park_gates.htm| title=Richmond Green properties: Old Palace Lane to the Old Deer Park Gates | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> Richmond Green and Little Green are overlooked by a mixture of period townhouses, historic buildings and municipal and commercial establishments including the Richmond Lending Library and [[Richmond Theatre]]. On summer weekends and public holidays the Green attracts many residents and visitors. It has a long history of hosting sporting events; from the 16th century onwards tournaments and [[archery]] contests have taken place on the Green, while [[cricket]] matches have occurred since the mid 18th century,<ref name=\"RG Local\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties.htm| title= Richmond Green: Properties| publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=17 September 2017}}</ref> continuing to the present day.\n\n==History and description==\n[[File:Richmond 20931.JPG|thumb|250px|Maids of Honour Row]]\n[[File:Railings at 11 Richmond Green.jpg|thumb|125px|Grade II* listed ornamental iron railings at 11, Richmond Green]]\n[[File:Fragment of the Old Palace, Richmond - geograph.org.uk - 508144.jpg|thumb|175px|Richmond Palace Gate House, which is Grade I listed]]\n[[Jousting]] tournaments took place on Richmond Green in the [[Middle Ages]], when English monarchs were living in or visiting what is now called Richmond.<ref name=\"Friends History\">{{cite web | url=http://www.forg.org.uk/history/ | title=History | publisher=Friends of Richmond Green | accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> For over 400 years, Richmond Green has been edged by houses and commercial premises&nbsp;\u2013 built to provide accommodation for people serving or visiting [[Richmond Palace]]. In 1625 [[Charles I of England|Charles I]] brought his court here to escape the [[Great Plague of London|plague in London]] and by the early 18th century these had become the homes of \"minor nobility, diplomats, and court hangers-on\".<ref name=\"RG Local\"/>\n\nThe construction of the railway in the mid-19th century cut the Green off from [[Old Deer Park]], and led to the building of Victorian [[villa]]s for the more prosperous commuters to London. The [[A316 road]], built in the early 20th century, worsened this separation.\n\nToday the northern, western and southern sides of the Green are residential while the eastern side, linking with Richmond's [[high street]], George Street, is largely retail and commercial. Public buildings line the eastern side of Little Green and pubs and caf\u00e9s cluster in the corner by Paved and Golden Courts&nbsp;\u2013 two of a number of alleys that lead from the Green to George Street. These alleys are lined with mostly privately owned [[boutique]]s.\n\nTo the west of the Green is Old Palace Lane, running gently down to the river.<ref>Robinson, Derek; Fowler, Simon (2017). ''Old Palace Lane: Medieval to Modern Richmond''. [[Richmond Local History Society]] and [[Museum of Richmond]]. {{ISBN|978-0-9550717-9-9}}.</ref> Adjoining to the left is the renowned terrace of well-preserved three-storey houses known as Maids of Honour Row. These were built in 1724 for the [[Maid of honour|maids of honour]] (trusted royal wardrobe servants) of [[Caroline of Ansbach|Queen Caroline]], the [[queen consort]] of [[George II of Great Britain|George II]]. As a child, [[Richard Francis Burton|Richard Burton]], the [[Victorian era|Victorian]] explorer, lived at number 2.<ref name=\"Burton\">{{cite web | url=  https://www.richmond.gov.uk/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/sir_richard_and_lady_isabel_burton| title=Sir Richard Burton (1821\u20131890) and Lady Isabel Burton (1831\u20131896) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local history notes | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=19 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Buildings==\nRichmond Green, usually \"The Green\", is also a street address. Numbers 1\u20136, 11\u201312 and 32, Richmond Green are all [[Listed buildings|Grade II* listed]].<ref name=\"1, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065311  |desc=1, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2-6, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065312  |desc=2\u20136, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"No. 11, and Railings\"/><ref name=\"12, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1181111  |desc=12, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"32, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357770  |desc=32, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> Numbers 7\u201310 Richmond Green are all Grade II listed,<ref name=\"Duke Street\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_duke_street_to_brewers_lane.htm | title=Richmond Green properties: Duke Street to Brewers Lane (Greenside) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"7, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065347  |desc=7, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"8 and 9, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1285176  |desc=8 and 9, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"10, Richmond Green\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357746  |desc=10, Richmond Green|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> as are nos 14\u201318, 21\u201325 and 29\u201331.<ref name=\"Brewers Lane\">{{cite web | url=http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties/richmond_green_brewers_lane_to_paved_court.htm | title=Richmond Green properties: Brewers Lane to Paved Court (Greenside) | publisher=[[London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]] | work=Local History Notes&nbsp;\u2013 Richmond Green: Properties | date=3 August 2009 | accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref> The [[Ironwork|ornamental iron]] railings at no 11 are Grade II* listed.<ref name=\"No. 11, and Railings\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065348  |desc=No. 11, and Railings|accessdate= 29 September 2016}}</ref> The Cricketers [[public house]] is between 24, Richmond Green and 25, Richmond Green. Another public house, The Prince's Head, is at 28, Richmond Green.<ref name=\"Duke Street\"/> 8, Richmond Green, is the location of the [[Richmond Charities]], which manages Richmond's [[almshouses]].\n\nThe late 19th-century [[drinking fountain]] at the south corner of Richmond Green and a pair of [[Red telephone box|K6 red telephone boxes]] are Grade II listed,<ref name=\"Fountain\"/><ref name=\"Kiosks\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1261332 |desc=Pair of K6 telephone kiosks|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref> as is a [[lamp standard]] outside 1, Richmond Green.<ref name=\"Lamp\">{{National Heritage List for England |num= 1357744 |desc=Lamp standard|accessdate= 12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe houses on the south-western side of the Green include Maids of Honour Row. The houses, and their gates and railings, at numbers 1\u20134 Maids of Honour Row are Grade I listed.<ref name=\"Maids of Honour list\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065317 |desc=Gates and Railings to Maids of Honour Row/Maids of Honour Row  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The Wardrobe and the Gate House, both [[Listed building|Grade I listed]],<ref name=\"Gate House listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065318 |desc=The Gate House The Old Palace  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Wardrobe listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357730 |desc=The Wardrobe  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> are surviving structures from [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]]'s [[Richmond Palace]]. The Gate House was built in 1501, and was let on a 65-year lease by the [[Crown Estate]] Commissioners in 1986. The Trumpeters' House, which is also Grade I listed,<ref name=\"Trumpeters' House listing\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357749 |desc=The Trumpeters' House, Old Palace Yard  |accessdate=9 July 2015}}</ref> is an early 18th-century house built on the site of Richmond Palace's Middle Gate.\n\nThe street bounding Richmond Green on the north-west is called Pembroke Villas, comprising 5 pairs of large semi-detached Victorian villas, formerly the site of the house of the Dutchman [[Sir Matthew Decker, 1st Baronet]] (1679-1749). It descended to his grandson [[Richard FitzWilliam, 7th Viscount FitzWilliam]] (1745-1816) of [[Mount Merrion]], Dublin, Ireland, who named it \"FitzWilliam House\" and there formed his famous art collection and by his will founded the [[Fitzwilliam Museum]] in Cambridge. The monument to Sir Matthew Decker and Richard FitzWilliam survives against the external wall of St Mary Magdalene's Church, Richmond. FitzWilliam's heir was his cousin [[George Herbert, 11th Earl of Pembroke]] (1759-1827), of [[Wilton House]] in Wiltshire, who renamed the house \"Pembroke House\". It was demolished in 1840.<ref>[https://www.richmond.gov.uk/richmond_green_old_palace_lane_to_the_old_deer_park_gates]</ref> \nNumbers 1 to 10, Pembroke Villas are Grade II listed.<ref name=\"Pembroke Villas 1-10\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1065319 |desc=Pembroke Villas  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> The street running along the north east of the Green, where it joins Pembroke Villas, is called Portland Terrace. Numbers 1 to 4, Portland Terrace are Grade II listed.<ref name=\"Portland Terrace 1-4\">{{National Heritage List for England |num=1357771|desc=Portland Terrace  |accessdate=19 September 2016}}</ref> Between Pembroke Villas and Portland Terrace is a gate that used to be the entrance to [[Old Deer Park]] and is now open only to pedestrians. Just a few yards beyond the gate, a footbridge crosses the railway to lead to Old Deer Park Car Park. Portland Terrace runs past Little Green to become Duke Street, where [[Duke Street Church, Richmond|Duke Street Church]] is located.\n\n==Cricket on the Green==\n{{Main article|Richmond Green cricket ground}}\n[[File:The Cricketers, The Green, Richmond, Surrey.jpg|thumb|125px|The Cricketers pub]]\nThe Green was a popular venue for [[cricket]] matches during the 18th century and before. The earliest reference to cricket on Richmond Green is from a 1666 letter by [[Sir Robert Paston]], a resident of Richmond.\n\nThe Green is presently home to two [[village cricket]] teams each affiliated to two of Richmond's [[public houses|pubs]], ''The Prince's Head'' and ''The Cricketers''. Midweek matches are contested in the modern limited overs format of [[Twenty20]] usually on a Tuesday or Thursdays, where surrounding village teams compete for the Len Smith Charity Shield.\n\n==Richmond Green in art==\nTwo [[watercolours]]  by Edward Walker, made in 1942, showing nos 10, 11 and 12 Richmond Green<ref name=\"V&A 1\">{{cite web | url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O596336/nos-10-11-12-richmond-watercolour-walker/#.U-eFHvkFGTM.facebook | title=Nos 10, 11 & 12 Richmond Green, Surrey; Recording Britain | publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] | work=Search the collections | accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> and the south side of the Green,<ref name=\"V&A 2\">{{cite web | url=https://collections.vam.ac.uk/item/O596335/south-side-of-the-green-drawing-walker/#.U-eEhbwI8d0.facebook | title=South Side of the Green, Richmond; Recording Britain | publisher=[[Victoria and Albert Museum]] | work=Search the collection | accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref> are in the [[Recording Britain]] collection at the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]].\n\n==Societies==\nThe Friends of Richmond Green, an amenity action group, seek to \"protect and enhance the Green for local residents, visitors and future generations\".<ref name=\"Friends\">{{cite web | url=http://www.forg.org.uk/ | title=Welcome to the Friends of Richmond Green | publisher=Friends of Richmond Green | accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery mode=packed heights=165 class=center>\nImage:Richmond Green 5260-6s.jpg|View of the northern half of Richmond Green, showing Pembroke Villas and Portland Terrace\nFile:Splendid Victorian Houses on Richmond Green, London-5057587834.jpg|Houses on Portland Terrace\nFile:Houses_At_Richmond_Green,_London-95369622.jpg|The south corner of Richmond Green\nFile:Richmond Green, London-geograph-2621535-by-Philip-Halling.jpg|Footpaths crossing Richmond Green\nFile:North side of Richmond Green-geograph-2498025-by-Marathon.jpg| Park Gates House, in Pembroke Villas, is next to the old entrance to [[Old Deer Park]]\n</gallery>\n[[Image:Map-richmondgreen.png|thumb|right|150px|Map of Richmond Green]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Richmond Green cricket ground]]\n*[[Richmond Green United Reformed Church]]\n*[[Richmond Palace]]\n*[[Richmond Theatre]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[John Cloake |Cloake, John]] (2001). ''Richmond Palace: Its History and Its Plan''. [[Richmond Local History Society]]. {{ISBN|978-0952209966}}.\n*[http://www.richmond.gov.uk/home/services/libraries/branch_libraries/local_studies_collection/local_history_notes/richmond_green_properties.htm \"Richmond Green properties\", Local history notes, Local Studies Collection, London Borough of Richmond upon Thames, 3 August 2009]\n* Robinson, Derek; Fowler, Simon (2017). ''Old Palace Lane: Medieval to Modern Richmond''. [[Richmond Local History Society]] and [[Museum of Richmond]]. {{ISBN|978-0-9550717-9-9}}.\n*{{cite book|title= The Streets of Richmond and Kew|edition= Third|date=2019|publisher = [[Richmond Local History Society]]}} 140 pages. {{ISBN|978-1912-314010}}.\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.forg.org.uk/ Friends of Richmond Green]\n* [http://www.richmondhistory.org.uk/ Richmond Local History Society]\n* [http://www.richmondsociety.org.uk/ The Richmond Society]\n\n{{LB Richmond}}\n{{Green London}}\n{{coord|51|27|42|N|0|18|25|W|type:landmark_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Conservation areas in London]]\n[[Category:Crown Estate]]\n[[Category:Drinking fountains in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Grade I listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Grade II listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Grade II* listed buildings in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Houses in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Jousting]]\n[[Category:Parks and open spaces in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n[[Category:Richmond, London]]\n[[Category:Streets in the London Borough of Richmond upon Thames]]\n", "name_user": "Headhitter", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Changed col width", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richmond_Green"}
{"title_page": "Ambedkar Memorial Park", "text_new": "{{short description|Public park and memorial in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{distinguish|Dr. B. R. Ambedkar Memorial Park}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Ambedkar Memorial Park\n| photo = Night_View_of_the_Ambedkar_Memorial_at_Lucknow.jpg\n| photo_width = 300\n| photo_caption =\n| type = Public, memorial park\n| location = [[Gomti Nagar]] in [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| map =\n| map_width =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| area = 108 acres (0.43&nbsp;km\u00b2)\n| opened = {{end date and age|df=y|2008|04|14}}\n| operator = Lucknow Development Authority\n| visitation_num =\n| status = Open year round\n| website =\n| coords= {{coord|26.848882|N|80.977893|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Ambedkar Memorial Park''', formally known as '''Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Prateek Sthal''',<ref name=\"Patel 2014\">{{cite web | last=Patel | first=Aakar | title=Where Ambedkar is enthroned like Lincoln | website=livemint.com | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/BlFbwHfSBGko9gt3nelyGI/Where-Ambedkar-is-enthroned-like-Lincoln.html | accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> is a public park and memorial in [[Gomti Nagar]], [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India. The memorial is dedicated to [[B. R. Ambedkar]], the 20th century Indian [[polymath]] and the \"father of the [[Constitution of India|Indian Constitution]]\". The park also honors the lives and memories of [[Jyotirao Phule]], [[Narayana Guru]], [[Birsa Munda]], [[Shahu of Kolhapur|Shahuji Maharaj]], [[Kanshi Ram]] and all those who've devoted their life for humanity, equality and social justice. The memorial was constructed by [[Mayawati]], the former [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]], during her administration when she led the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar.jpg|right|thumb|The memorial is dedicated to [[B. R. Ambedkar]].]]\nThe foundation stone of the memorial was first laid in 1995. Earlier, the park was named Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Udyan. In 2002, it was renamed the Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial and development work continued until 2002-03. In 2007, the park underwent further renovation and development. It was initially opened to the public on 14 April 2008 by Chief Minister Mayawati.\n\nThe entire memorial is built using red [[sandstone]] brought from [[Rajasthan]]. It is situated in the posh locality of Gomti Nagar, the largest planned residential colony in India. Cost of the memorial is estimated at 7&nbsp;billion [[Indian rupee|rupees]].<ref>[http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/ambedkar-memorial-in-lucknow-to-cost-seven-billion-rupees_10024390.html Ambedkar Memorial in Lucknow to cost seven billion rupees], Thaindian News, 5 March 2008, 7:54&nbsp;pm</ref> Its name was changed from Ambedkar Park to Bhimrao Ambedkar memorial in May 2012.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-05-19/lucknow/27117237_1_ambedkar-memorial-lda-officials-chief-secretary It\u2019s now Ambedkar Memorial, not park], ''[[The Times of India]]'', TNN, 19 May 2002, 11.57&nbsp;pm IST</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThere are several sites comprising the memorial park.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://sites.google.com/site/lucknowtravelguide/ambedkar-memorial-lucknow | title=Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Sthal in Lucknow -UP- India -Latest Description and Photos - Lucknow Travel Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Ambedkar Stupa===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Ambedkar Stupa.JPG\n| width1 = 180\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = Ambedkar Stupa\n| image2 = Ambedkar Stupa Night view.JPG\n| width2 = 180\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = Ambedkar Stupa Night view\n| footer = \n}}\n[[File:The bronze statue of BR Ambedkar in Ambedkar Memorial Park, Lucknow, identical to Lincoln's.jpg|right|thumb|upright|The bronze statue of Ambedkar in Ambedkar Memorial; the base is inscribed \"''My struggle of life is my only message.''\" The Ambedkar statue was modeled on the [[Abraham Lincoln (1920 statue)|sculpture of Abraham Lincoln]] at the [[Lincoln Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].]]\n\nThis construction is the heart of the entire memorial. The sanctum sanctorum consists of many statues depicting the biography of Ambedkar. There are four doors in opposite directions. This is a construction in the shape of a flower bearing four petals. There is a bronze statue of Ambedkar seated in a chair, facing towards the two domes. The Ambedkar statue was modeled on the [[Abraham Lincoln (1920 statue)|sculpture of Abraham Lincoln]] at the [[Lincoln Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Belli|first=Melia|date=2014|title=Monumental Pride: Mayawati's Memorials in Lucknow|journal=Ars Orientalis|volume=44|issue=20181025|doi=10.3998/ars.13441566.0044.006|issn=2328-1286|hdl=2027/spo.13441566.0044.006|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nAt the base of the statue a message in Hindi reads:\n\n{{cquote|<center>\n'''\u092e\u0947\u0930\u093e \u091c\u0940\u0935\u0928 \u0938\u0902\u0918\u0930\u094d\u0937 \u0939\u0940 \u092e\u0947\u0930\u093e \u0938\u0902\u0926\u0947\u0936 \u0939\u0948'''<br />\n(''Mera jeevan sangharsh hi mera sandesh hai'')<br />\n''My struggle of life is my only message.''\n</center>|30px|30px}}\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Sangrahalay===\nOpposite to the Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial is the Sangrahalay ([[museum]]), constructed over an area of about 2.5 acre (11,008 sq.m.). The building has two domes on top. It contains large statues of Mahatma Jyotiba Phule, Rajarshi Chhatrapati Shahuji Maharaj, Shri Narayan Guru, Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar and Shri Kanshiram. Another building consists of 18-foot tall marble statues of [[Tath\u0101gata|Tathagat Gautam Buddha]], [[Kabir|Sant Kabir Das]], [[Sant Ravidas]], [[Ghasidas|Guru Ghasidas]] and [[Birsa Munda|Shri Birsa Munda]].\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Gallery===\nConstructed in an area of 4 acres (16,207 sq.m.), this place has murals made of bronze.\n\n===Pratibimb Sthal===\n[[File:Pratibimb Sthal.JPG|thumb|right|Pratibimb Sthal]]\nPratibimb Sthal is the main entrance to the memorial guarded by statues of 62 elephants either side.\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial Drashya Sthal===\nConstructed on an 80-foot pyramid type structure on the back of Pratibimb Sthal, the Drashya Sthal offers a vantage point from where the park, shrines, structures and sites integrate as a view of the whole area. The flow of water from the top of the pyramid entertains visitors.\n\n==Memorial in legal battle==\nSince 2009 the memorial has been involved in a legal battle. In June 2009 the Supreme Court issued a stay against further building on the project, until the [[Public Interest Litigation]] (PLI) questioning these expenditure was settled.<ref name=\"Nair\">{{Cite news|author=Nair, Harish V.|date=24 January 2015 |title=Akhilesh gets Supreme rap in statues case |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2924817/Akhilesh-gets-Supreme-rap-statues-case.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150125143534/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2924817/Akhilesh-gets-Supreme-rap-statues-case.html |archivedate=25 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite initially denying even maintenance costs,<ref>{{Cite news|title=SC declines maintenance plea at Ambedkar memorial |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=1 December 2009 |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sc-declines-maintenance-plea-at-ambedkar-memorial/548485/0 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmszM77x?url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/sc-declines-maintenance-plea-at-ambedkar-memorial/548485/0 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Court rejects Mayawati's plea on Ambedkar memorial |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=1 December 2009 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article57958.ece |archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1443118548FDBSNXDRSY?url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article57958.ece |archivedate=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> in December 2010, the Uttar Pradesh government received permission to perform maintenance and completion of the park.<ref name=\"Nair\" /><ref name=\"Foy\">{{Cite news|author=Foy, Henry |date=4 December 2010 |title=Statutes and statues: Mayawati gets Supreme Court nod for sprawling memorial park |newspaper=Reuters |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2010/12/04/statutes-and-statues-mayawati-gets-supreme-court-nod-for-sprawling-memorial-park/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmk8hIDc?url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2010/12/04/statutes-and-statues-mayawati-gets-supreme-court-nod-for-sprawling-memorial-park/ |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, as of 2015, the lawsuit was still ongoing.<ref name=\"Nair\" />\n\n==Vandalism==\nOn 26 July 2012 a statue in the park was damaged by members of a group calling themselves \"Uttar Pradesh Nav Nirman Sena\".<ref>{{Cite news|date=28 July 2012 |title=Maya statue vandalisation case: Prime accused Amit Jani arrested |newspaper=Jagran Post (Jagran Prakashan Ltd) |location=Kanpur |url=http://post.jagran.com/Maya-statue-vandalisation-case-Prime-accused-Amit-Jani-arrested-1343462432 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmr7nFRc?url=http://post.jagran.com/Maya-statue-vandalisation-case-Prime-accused-Amit-Jani-arrested-1343462432 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"Stat-dam\">{{Cite news|title=Mayawati's statue damaged, CM condemns attack |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=26 July 2012 |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/mayawati-s-statue-damaged-in-lucknow-3-held/story-KeGCTsYm1jMRHbLvV25EVK.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmv7TNox?url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/mayawati-s-statue-damaged-in-lucknow-3-held/story-KeGCTsYm1jMRHbLvV25EVK.html |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> A replacement statue was re-installed overnight by the Lucknow city administration.<ref>{{Cite news|date=27 July 2015 |title=UP city administration replaces Mayawati statues overnight in Lucknow |newspaper=Jagran Post (Jagran Prakashan Ltd) |location=Kanpur |url=http://post.jagran.com/UP-city-administration-replaces-Mayawati-statues-overnight-in-Lucknow-1343382213 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmrae1Yd?url=http://post.jagran.com/UP-city-administration-replaces-Mayawati-statues-overnight-in-Lucknow-1343382213 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"Tripathi\">{{Cite news|last=Tripathi |first=Ashish |date=27 July 2012 |title=Political compulsion makes SP govt reinstall Mayawati's statue |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-27/lucknow/32888171_1_new-statue-dalit-icons-bsp-founder-kanshiram |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmuNE7Vz?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Political-compulsion-makes-SP-govt-reinstall-Mayawatis-statue/articleshow/15192030.cms?referral=PM |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Film shooting==\nIn the [[Bollywood]] film ''[[Youngistaan]]'' (2014) actors [[Jackky Bhagnani]] and [[Neha Sharma]] shot in Ambedkar Memorial Park and were surprised with its vast scale.<ref name=\"Akash WadhwaAkash Wadhwa 2015\">{{cite web | last=Akash WadhwaAkash Wadhwa | first=TNN | title=Ambedkar park - it doesn't get grander than this | website=The Times of India | date=20 September 2015 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Ambedkar-park-it-doesnt-get-grander-than-this/articleshow/49032827.cms | accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref> After permission for shooting outside the memorial in March 2014, [[Aditya Roy Kapur]] and [[Parineeti Chopra]] shot for \"Rangreli\" song of film ''[[Daawat-e-Ishq]]''.<ref name=\"Misra 2014\">{{cite web | last=Misra | first=Iti Shree | title=College classes suspended for Parineeti Chopra and Aditya Roy Kapur's 'Dawaat-e-Ishq' | website=The Times of India | date=5 March 2014 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/College-classes-suspended-for-Parineeti-Chopra-and-Aditya-Roy-Kapurs-shoot/articleshow/31469166.cms | accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, [[Ravi Kishan]] shot for a Bhojpuri film at Ambedkar Memorial Park. In February 2016, [[Mika Singh]] and [[Urvashi Rautela]] also shot for their new music video named ''Lal Dupatta Kurta Chikan Ka'' just outside the Memorial<ref name=\"mid-day 2016\">{{cite web | title=Urvashi Rautela shoots for Mika Singh's new music video | website=mid-day | date=21 February 2016 | url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/urvashi-rautela-shoots-for-mika-singhs-new-music-video/16974154 | accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In 2017, the song \"Jogi\" from the movie ''[[Shaadi Mein Zaroor Aana]]'', starring [[Rajkumar Rao]] and [[Kriti Kharbanda]] was shot here. In 2017 small part of Movie ''[[Bareilly Ki Barfi]]'' starring [[Ayushman Khurrana]], Rajkummar Rao and [[Kriti Sanon]] was also shot here.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Ambedkar Park Lucknow.JPG|Inside view of Ambedkar park in night\nFile:B.R. Ambedkar statue at Ambedkar Park.JPG|Statue of B.R. Ambedkar inside Ambedkar Park, Lucknow\nFile:Ambedkar Udyaan Lucknow Left Dome.JPG|Morning view of park\nFile:The Middle Portion with the right Dome in the Backdrop.JPG|Night view\nFile:Right Side Pillers at the entrance.jpg|Pillars at night view\nFile:Ambedkar Park, Lucknow, India.jpg|View from outside\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of statues of B. R. Ambedkar]]\n* [[Statue of Equality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ambedkar Memorial Park}}\n* [http://wikimapia.org/134882/Ambedkar-Memorial-Gomti-Nagar Ambedkar Memorial, Gomti Nagar @ Wikimapia]\n* [https://www.panoramio.com/photo/19420771 Photos of Ambedkar Udyan Memorial, Lucknow, Uttar Pradesh @ panoramia]\n* [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-06-21/lucknow/27319566_1_gate-ambedkar-memorial-ticket-counters The saga of Ambedkar memorial], [[The Times of India]], TNN, 21 June 2002, 12.36&nbsp;am IST\n* [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/thousands-throng-ambedkar-memorial/550767/ Thousands throng Ambedkar Memorial], [[Indian Express]], Express News Service, Mon 7 December 2009, 01:47 hrs\n\n{{Lucknow}}\n\n[[Category:Dalit monuments]]\n[[Category:Bahujan Samaj Party]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lucknow]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Memorials to B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lucknow]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 2008]]\n[[Category:Statues of B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Things named after B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Memorial parks]]\n[[Category:Sculpture gardens, trails and parks in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Public park and memorial in Uttar Pradesh, India}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{distinguish|Dr. B. R. Ambedkar Memorial Park}}\n{{Infobox park\n| name = Ambedkar Memorial Park\n| photo = Night_View_of_the_Ambedkar_Memorial_at_Lucknow.jpg\n| photo_width = 300\n| photo_caption =\n| type = Public, memorial park\n| location = [[Gomti Nagar]] in [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| map =\n| map_width =\n| map_alt =\n| map_caption =\n| area = 108 acres (0.43 km\u00b2)\n| opened = {{end date and age|df=y|2008|04|14}}\n| operator = Lucknow Development Authority\n| visitation_num =\n| status = Open year round\n| website =\n| coords= {{coord|26.848882|N|80.977893|E|format=dms|display=inline,title}}\n}}\n\n'''Ambedkar Memorial Park''', formally known as '''Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Prateek Sthal''',<ref name=\"Patel 2014\">{{cite web | last=Patel | first=Aakar | title=Where Ambedkar is enthroned like Lincoln | website=livemint.com | date=13 September 2014 | url=http://www.livemint.com/Leisure/BlFbwHfSBGko9gt3nelyGI/Where-Ambedkar-is-enthroned-like-Lincoln.html | accessdate=21 October 2015}}</ref> is a public park and memorial in [[Gomti Nagar]], [[Lucknow]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], India. The memorial is dedicated to [[B. R. Ambedkar]], the 20th century Indian [[polymath]] and the \"father of the [[Constitution of India|Indian Constitution]]\". The park also honors the lives and memories of [[Jyotirao Phule]], [[Narayana Guru]], [[Birsa Munda]], [[Shahu of Kolhapur|Shahuji Maharaj]], [[Kanshi Ram]] and all those who've devoted their life for humanity, equality and social justice. The memorial was constructed by [[Mayawati]], the former [[Chief Minister of Uttar Pradesh]], during her administration when she led the [[Bahujan Samaj Party]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar.jpg|right|thumb|The memorial is dedicated to [[B. R. Ambedkar]].]]\nThe foundation stone of the memorial was first laid in 1995. Earlier, the park was named Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Udyan. In 2002, it was renamed the Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial and development work continued until 2002-03. In 2007, the park underwent further renovation and development. It was initially opened to the public on 14 April 2008 by Chief Minister Mayawati.\n\nThe entire memorial is built using red [[sandstone]] brought from [[Rajasthan]]. It is situated in the posh locality of Gomti Nagar, the largest planned residential colony in India. Cost of the memorial is estimated at 7 billion [[Indian rupee|rupees]].<ref>[http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/india-news/ambedkar-memorial-in-lucknow-to-cost-seven-billion-rupees_10024390.html Ambedkar Memorial in Lucknow to cost seven billion rupees], Thaindian News, 5 March 2008, 7:54 pm</ref> Its name was changed from Ambedkar Park to Bhimrao Ambedkar memorial in May 2012.<ref>[http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-05-19/lucknow/27117237_1_ambedkar-memorial-lda-officials-chief-secretary It\u2019s now Ambedkar Memorial, not park], ''[[The Times of India]]'', TNN, 19 May 2002, 11.57pm IST</ref>\n\n==Features==\nThere are several sites comprising the memorial park.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://sites.google.com/site/lucknowtravelguide/ambedkar-memorial-lucknow | title=Dr. Bhim Rao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Sthal in Lucknow -UP- India -Latest Description and Photos - Lucknow Travel Guide}}</ref>\n\n===Ambedkar Stupa===\n{{multiple image\n| align = right\n| image1 = Ambedkar Stupa.JPG\n| width1 = 180\n| alt1 = \n| caption1 = Ambedkar Stupa\n| image2 = Ambedkar Stupa Night view.JPG\n| width2 = 180\n| alt2 = \n| caption2 = Ambedkar Stupa Night view\n| footer = \n}}\n[[File:The bronze statue of BR Ambedkar in Ambedkar Memorial Park, Lucknow, identical to Lincoln's.jpg|right|thumb|upright|The bronze statue of Ambedkar in Ambedkar Memorial; the base is inscribed \"''My struggle of life is my only message.''\" The Ambedkar statue was modeled on the [[Abraham Lincoln (1920 statue)|sculpture of Abraham Lincoln]] at the [[Lincoln Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.]].]]\n\nThis construction is the heart of the entire memorial. The sanctum sanctorum consists of many statues depicting the biography of Ambedkar. There are four doors in opposite directions. This is a construction in the shape of a flower bearing four petals. There is a bronze statue of Ambedkar seated in a chair, facing towards the two domes. The Ambedkar statue was modeled on the [[Abraham Lincoln (1920 statue)|sculpture of Abraham Lincoln]] at the [[Lincoln Memorial]] in [[Washington, D.C.|Washington]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Belli|first=Melia|date=2014|title=Monumental Pride: Mayawati's Memorials in Lucknow|journal=Ars Orientalis|volume=44|issue=20181025|doi=10.3998/ars.13441566.0044.006|issn=2328-1286|hdl=2027/spo.13441566.0044.006|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nAt the base of the statue a message in Hindi reads:\n\n{{cquote|<center>\n'''\u092e\u0947\u0930\u093e \u091c\u0940\u0935\u0928 \u0938\u0902\u0918\u0930\u094d\u0937 \u0939\u0940 \u092e\u0947\u0930\u093e \u0938\u0902\u0926\u0947\u0936 \u0939\u0948'''<br />\n(''Mera jeevan sangharsh hi mera sandesh hai'')<br />\n''My struggle of life is my only message.''\n</center>|30px|30px}}\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Sangrahalay===\nOpposite to the Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial is the Sangrahalay ([[museum]]), constructed over an area of about 2.5 acre (11,008 sq.m.). The building has two domes on top. It contains large statues of Mahatma Jyotiba Phule, Rajarshi Chhatrapati Shahuji Maharaj, Shri Narayan Guru, Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar and Shri Kanshiram. Another building consists of 18-foot tall marble statues of [[Tath\u0101gata|Tathagat Gautam Buddha]], [[Kabir|Sant Kabir Das]], [[Sant Ravidas]], [[Ghasidas|Guru Ghasidas]] and [[Birsa Munda|Shri Birsa Munda]].\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Samajik Parivartan Gallery===\nConstructed in an area of 4 acres (16,207 sq.m.), this place has murals made of bronze.\n\n===Pratibimb Sthal===\n[[File:Pratibimb Sthal.JPG|thumb|right|Pratibimb Sthal]]\nPratibimb Sthal is the main entrance to the memorial guarded by statues of 62 elephants either side.\n\n===Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar Memorial Drashya Sthal===\nConstructed on an 80-foot pyramid type structure on the back of Pratibimb Sthal, the Drashya Sthal offers a vantage point from where the park, shrines, structures and sites integrate as a view of the whole area. The flow of water from the top of the pyramid entertains visitors.\n\n==Memorial in legal battle==\nSince 2009 the memorial has been involved in a legal battle. In June 2009 the Supreme Court issued a stay against further building on the project, until the [[Public Interest Litigation]] (PLI) questioning these expenditure was settled.<ref name=\"Nair\">{{Cite news|author=Nair, Harish V.|date=24 January 2015 |title=Akhilesh gets Supreme rap in statues case |newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2924817/Akhilesh-gets-Supreme-rap-statues-case.html |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20150125143534/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/indiahome/indianews/article-2924817/Akhilesh-gets-Supreme-rap-statues-case.html |archivedate=25 January 2015 |url-status=live}}</ref> Despite initially denying even maintenance costs,<ref>{{Cite news|title=SC declines maintenance plea at Ambedkar memorial |newspaper=[[The Indian Express]] |date=1 December 2009 |url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/sc-declines-maintenance-plea-at-ambedkar-memorial/548485/0 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmszM77x?url=http://archive.indianexpress.com/news/sc-declines-maintenance-plea-at-ambedkar-memorial/548485/0 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Court rejects Mayawati's plea on Ambedkar memorial |newspaper=[[The Hindu]] |date=1 December 2009 |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article57958.ece |archiveurl=http://www.freezepage.com/1443118548FDBSNXDRSY?url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/article57958.ece |archivedate=24 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> in December 2010, the Uttar Pradesh government received permission to perform maintenance and completion of the park.<ref name=\"Nair\" /><ref name=\"Foy\">{{Cite news|author=Foy, Henry |date=4 December 2010 |title=Statutes and statues: Mayawati gets Supreme Court nod for sprawling memorial park |newspaper=Reuters |url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2010/12/04/statutes-and-statues-mayawati-gets-supreme-court-nod-for-sprawling-memorial-park/ |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmk8hIDc?url=http://blogs.reuters.com/india/2010/12/04/statutes-and-statues-mayawati-gets-supreme-court-nod-for-sprawling-memorial-park/ |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> However, as of 2015, the lawsuit was still ongoing.<ref name=\"Nair\" />\n\n==Vandalism==\nOn 26 July 2012 a statue in the park was damaged by members of a group calling themselves \"Uttar Pradesh Nav Nirman Sena\".<ref>{{Cite news|date=28 July 2012 |title=Maya statue vandalisation case: Prime accused Amit Jani arrested |newspaper=Jagran Post (Jagran Prakashan Ltd) |location=Kanpur |url=http://post.jagran.com/Maya-statue-vandalisation-case-Prime-accused-Amit-Jani-arrested-1343462432 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmr7nFRc?url=http://post.jagran.com/Maya-statue-vandalisation-case-Prime-accused-Amit-Jani-arrested-1343462432 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"Stat-dam\">{{Cite news|title=Mayawati's statue damaged, CM condemns attack |newspaper=Hindustan Times |date=26 July 2012 |url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/mayawati-s-statue-damaged-in-lucknow-3-held/story-KeGCTsYm1jMRHbLvV25EVK.html |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmv7TNox?url=http://www.hindustantimes.com/lucknow/mayawati-s-statue-damaged-in-lucknow-3-held/story-KeGCTsYm1jMRHbLvV25EVK.html |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref> A replacement statue was re-installed overnight by the Lucknow city administration.<ref>{{Cite news|date=27 July 2015 |title=UP city administration replaces Mayawati statues overnight in Lucknow |newspaper=Jagran Post (Jagran Prakashan Ltd) |location=Kanpur |url=http://post.jagran.com/UP-city-administration-replaces-Mayawati-statues-overnight-in-Lucknow-1343382213 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmrae1Yd?url=http://post.jagran.com/UP-city-administration-replaces-Mayawati-statues-overnight-in-Lucknow-1343382213 |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref><ref name=\"Tripathi\">{{Cite news|last=Tripathi |first=Ashish |date=27 July 2012 |title=Political compulsion makes SP govt reinstall Mayawati's statue |newspaper=[[The Times of India]] |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-27/lucknow/32888171_1_new-statue-dalit-icons-bsp-founder-kanshiram |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6bmuNE7Vz?url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/lucknow/Political-compulsion-makes-SP-govt-reinstall-Mayawatis-statue/articleshow/15192030.cms?referral=PM |archivedate=24 September 2015 |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\n==Film shooting==\nIn the [[Bollywood]] film ''[[Youngistaan]]'' (2014) actors [[Jackky Bhagnani]] and [[Neha Sharma]] shot in Ambedkar Memorial Park and were surprised with its vast scale.<ref name=\"Akash WadhwaAkash Wadhwa 2015\">{{cite web | last=Akash WadhwaAkash Wadhwa | first=TNN | title=Ambedkar park - it doesn't get grander than this | website=The Times of India | date=20 September 2015 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Ambedkar-park-it-doesnt-get-grander-than-this/articleshow/49032827.cms | accessdate=30 September 2015}}</ref> After permission for shooting outside the memorial in March 2014, [[Aditya Roy Kapur]] and [[Parineeti Chopra]]  shot for \"Rangreli\" song of film ''[[Daawat-e-Ishq]]''.<ref name=\"Misra 2014\">{{cite web | last=Misra | first=Iti Shree | title=College classes suspended for Parineeti Chopra and Aditya Roy Kapur's 'Dawaat-e-Ishq' | website=The Times of India | date=5 March 2014 | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/College-classes-suspended-for-Parineeti-Chopra-and-Aditya-Roy-Kapurs-shoot/articleshow/31469166.cms | accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, [[Ravi Kishan]] shot for a Bhojpuri film at Ambedkar Memorial Park. In February 2016, [[Mika Singh]] and [[Urvashi Rautela]] also shot for their new music video named ''Lal Dupatta Kurta Chikan Ka'' just outside the Memorial <ref name=\"mid-day 2016\">{{cite web | title=Urvashi Rautela shoots for Mika Singh's new music video | website=mid-day | date=21 February 2016 | url=http://www.mid-day.com/articles/urvashi-rautela-shoots-for-mika-singhs-new-music-video/16974154 | accessdate=20 April 2016}}</ref> In 2017, the song \"Jogi\" from the movie ''[[Shaadi Mein Zaroor Aana]]'', starring [[Rajkumar Rao]] and [[Kriti Kharbanda]] was shot here. In 2017 small part of Movie ''[[Bareilly Ki Barfi]]'' starring [[Ayushman Khurrana]], Rajkummar Rao and [[Kriti Sanon]] was also shot here.{{cn|date=August 2019}}\n\n==Gallery==\n<gallery>\nFile:Ambedkar Park Lucknow.JPG|Inside view of Ambedkar park in night\nFile:B.R. Ambedkar statue at Ambedkar Park.JPG|Statue of B.R. Ambedkar inside Ambedkar Park, Lucknow\nFile:Ambedkar Udyaan Lucknow Left Dome.JPG|Morning view of park\nFile:The Middle Portion with the right Dome in the Backdrop.JPG|Night view\nFile:Right Side Pillers at the entrance.jpg|Pillars at night view\nFile:Ambedkar Park, Lucknow, India.jpg|View from outside\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of statues of B. R. Ambedkar]]\n* [[Statue of Equality]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Ambedkar Memorial Park}}\n* [http://wikimapia.org/134882/Ambedkar-Memorial-Gomti-Nagar Ambedkar Memorial, Gomti Nagar @ Wikimapia]\n* [https://www.panoramio.com/photo/19420771 Photos of Ambedkar Udyan Memorial, Lucknow, Uttar Pradesh @ panoramia]\n* [http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2002-06-21/lucknow/27319566_1_gate-ambedkar-memorial-ticket-counters The saga of Ambedkar memorial], [[The Times of India]], TNN, 21 June 2002, 12.36am IST\n* [http://www.indianexpress.com/news/thousands-throng-ambedkar-memorial/550767/ Thousands throng Ambedkar Memorial], [[Indian Express]], Express News Service, Mon 7 December 2009, 01:47 hrs\n\n{{Lucknow}}\n\n[[Category:Dalit monuments]]\n[[Category:Bahujan Samaj Party]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Lucknow]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:Memorials to B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Lucknow]]\n[[Category:2008 establishments in India]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures completed in 2008]]\n[[Category:Statues of B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Things named after B. R. Ambedkar]]\n[[Category:Memorial parks]]\n[[Category:Sculpture gardens, trails and parks in India]]\n", "name_user": "Fylindfotberserk", "label": "safe", "comment": "Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedi